## **Chapter 1** **THE PROBLEM AND ITS BACKGROUND**

### **1.1 Introduction**

American Hospital Inc. is a private medical facility in Intramuros, Manila specializing in pre-employment medical examinations for workers requiring overseas deployment certification. The clinic operates with 45 employees across ten functional departments: reception, billing, cashier, laboratory, radiology, electrocardiography, psychology, dental, physical examination, and releasing. The facility processes approximately 1,000 pre-employment medical examinations monthly, with daily patient volume averaging 50 examinations ranging from 30 to 35 patients during low-demand periods to 60 to 70 patients during peak periods. The clinic maintains an active patient database containing 50,000 to 70,000 records.

The organization holds ISO 9001:2015 certification for quality management and maintains regulatory compliance with Department of Health standards and Data Privacy Act requirements under Republic Act No. 10173\. The facility serves multiple international maritime authorities and recruitment agencies, processing approximately 900 regular pre-employment medical examinations monthly with 72-hour completion targets and 100 rush examinations monthly with 24-hour completion targets. Additionally, the clinic conducts 600 to 700 monthly re-medical examinations for workers requiring periodic health assessments.

The clinic operates a Computer Information System with modules supporting admission processing, billing management, laboratory results recording across multiple testing units, radiology and ultrasound reporting, electrocardiography recording, audiometry documentation, psychological test evaluation, triage assessment, and result releasing coordination. This partial computerization coexists with paper-based monitoring forms, charge slips, and manual logbooks used throughout the examination workflow.

### **1.2 Statement of the Problem**

American Hospital Inc. manages pre-employment medical examinations through a paper-based and department-segmented system. Clinical staff in different units record findings and transmit information through forms, charge slips, and manual logbooks. The releasing unit consolidates results from all clinical departments to prepare final examination certificates. This process requires manual status verification across departments, repeated data handling, and staff initiative to determine when a case is complete and ready for final review.

Result collation encounters 224 documented incidents monthly. Staff must manually check all departments to confirm completion status, consuming 50 to 85 minutes of staff time daily. Laboratory results account for 85 monthly pending cases, radiology incomplete submissions total 64 monthly cases, psychology unscored examinations reach 43 monthly cases, ECG pending results represent 21 monthly cases, and dental or physical examination incomplete submissions total 11 monthly cases. Completed results remain idle for 1 to 3 hours after actual completion because releasing staff have no systematic notification when departments finish their work.

Encoding and transcription encounter 160 documented incidents monthly. Manual transcription incidents total 60 monthly cases. Historical retrieval for 600 to 700 monthly re-medical examinations requires 15 to 45 minutes per case because staff must search through physical files or navigate unintegrated digital archives. All patient information is entered twice: once when service departments record findings, and again when releasing staff compile final certificates.

These operational problems produce measurable performance gaps. Patient waiting time averages 2.6 hours across all departments, with laboratory wait times reaching 65 minutes during peak periods and radiology reaching 55 minutes. Regular pre-employment medical examinations fail to meet the 72-hour completion target in 8 percent of cases, totaling 72 monthly failures and 864 annual failures. Rush examinations fail to meet the 24-hour completion target in 10 to 11 percent of cases, totaling 11 monthly failures and 132 annual failures. Certificate errors occur at rates of 5 to 6 percent, producing 53 to 64 errors monthly and 636 to 768 errors annually. Encoding errors represent 26 monthly incidents, transcription errors represent 21 monthly incidents, and collation errors represent 11 monthly incidents.

Agencies submit 50 to 65 status inquiries weekly, averaging 8 to 10 daily requests that consume 55 to 85 minutes of staff time daily. Formal complaints occur 4 to 6 times monthly, and informal concerns arise 10 to 15 times monthly. Agency dissatisfaction affects 15 to 20 percent of clients. Patients have no direct visibility into their own examination progress and must ask staff or wait for verbal updates to determine which tests remain pending.

The operational problems translate into quantifiable financial losses. Direct measurable annual loss totals PHP 441,000 to 667,000 from operational inefficiency. Operational inefficiency costs break down into result collation checking consuming PHP 43,000 to 68,000 annually, status inquiry management consuming PHP 44,000 to 68,000 annually, error correction cycles consuming PHP 127,000 to 154,000 annually, and historical retrieval consuming PHP 77,000 annually. Client attrition reaches 0 to 1 agency annually representing PHP 150,000 to 300,000 loss per departed agency.

Timeline failures total 2,436 incidents annually, comprising 864 regular examination late completions, 132 rush examination late completions, and 1,440 releasing delays. These failures cause deployment delays affecting 17 to 26 patients monthly or 204 to 312 patients annually. Patient churn reaches 4 percent monthly, totaling 36 patients monthly or 432 patients annually who abandon the examination process after initial visit.

The cumulative impact compounds over time. Three-year projections show 7,308 late completions, 1,908 to 2,304 certificate errors, 612 to 936 patients affected by deployment delays, 1,296 patients lost to churn, and 0 to 3 agencies at risk, totaling PHP 1,323,000 to 2,001,000 in revenue loss. Five-year projections show 12,180 late completions, 3,180 to 3,840 certificate errors, 1,020 to 1,560 patients affected by deployment delays, 2,160 patients lost to churn, and 0 to 5 agencies at risk, totaling PHP 2,200,000 to 3,300,000 in revenue loss.

The structural problem is the absence of real-time visibility into patient progress and examination status. Staff cannot determine case status without manually checking each department. Agencies cannot access progress information without calling or emailing clinic staff. Patients cannot track their own examination progress or verify result availability. This creates coordination problems that extend patient waiting time, delay result availability, burden staff with repeated status confirmations, and produce errors through multiple manual data handling steps.

### **1.3 Objectives of the Study**

#### **1.3.1 General Objective**

To develop a monitoring and result access solution that addresses operational problems in pre-employment medical examination tracking, patient flow visibility and examination status, and result release at American Hospital Inc.

#### **1.3.2 Specific Objectives**

* To design a centralized system workflow that actively tracks patient status across all relevant clinical departments, bridging the communication gaps between standalone units through real-time data encoding, automated queue management, and integrated result collation.  
* To implement the project as a modern, responsive web-based application utilizing a cloud-native architecture, featuring secure user accounts, real-time staff dashboards, active clinical data encoding interfaces, and a mobile-responsive external portal for automated result access and email notifications.  
* To test the system against FURPS+ requirements framework, verifying functional suitability through feature completeness testing, usability through System Usability Scale (SUS) administration (Hyzy et al., 2022\) and task completion metrics, reliability through uptime monitoring and error rate measurement, performance through response time testing and load simulation, and supportability through code quality review and documentation assessment.  
* To evaluate the system for compliance with ISO 9001:2015 quality management standards through structured audit procedures, Department of Health medical information system requirements through verification checklists, Data Privacy Act provisions through security and privacy controls assessment, and ISO/IEC 25010:2023 software quality characteristics through systematic quality attribute evaluation.


### **1.4 Scope and Limitation of the Study**

The study addresses pre-employment medical examination workflows at American Hospital Inc. in Intramuros, Manila. The clinic processes 1,000 monthly cases across ten departments, employs 45 staff members, serves approximately 1,000 monthly external users including recruitment agencies and individual patients, and maintains 50,000 to 70,000 active patient records.

Data parameters include patient demographics, examination transaction identifiers, assigned package types, department status indicators, actively encoded clinical results from all service units, fitness-to-work conclusions, certificate generation, and audit records. The system functions as a specialized, parallel Electronic Medical Record (EMR) module dedicated strictly to PEME workflows. Rather than passively reading from legacy systems, clinical and departmental staff will encode PEME-specific examination findings directly into the new system to trigger real-time queue updates and automate result collation.

System deliverables include a web-based Single Page Application (SPA) deployed via modern cloud infrastructure, paired with a secure Backend-as-a-Service (BaaS). The staff dashboard provides real-time patient status monitoring and department queue visualization with WebSocket-driven live updates. The external portal provides secure authentication enabling recruitment agency representatives and patients to track examination progress and securely download finalized results through a mobile-first, responsive interface.

Additional deliverables include database implementation supporting the full patient record dataset with normalized schema design, user account management with role-based permissions distinguishing staff users, individual patient users, and agency representative users, read-only integration connectors accessing data from existing Computer Information System modules for admission, billing, laboratory, radiology, ultrasound, ECG, audiometry, psychology, and triage, logic mapping completed examinations against package-defined requirements to determine progress status, and automated email notification system that alerts releasing staff when results are uploaded to the portal, notifies agency representatives when their workers' results become available, and notifies individual patients when their examination results are ready for access.

Testing procedures verify functional completeness through systematic test case execution covering all core workflows including staff case monitoring, patient progress tracking, agency result access, automated status aggregation from CIS modules, and email notification delivery. Usability assessment employs System Usability Scale administration (Hyzy et al., 2022\) to three user groups comprising staff dashboard users, individual patient portal users, and agency representative portal users, with task-based completion metrics measuring time to locate case status, view examination progress, and access results. Performance testing measures page load times, concurrent user load simulation representing 20 to 30 staff users and 50 to 100 external users, database query performance across the full patient dataset, real-time status aggregation response times, and email notification delivery times. Reliability monitoring tracks system uptime and error frequency measurement.

Evaluation procedures assess compliance with multiple regulatory frameworks and quality standards. ISO 9001:2015 quality management standards compliance uses structured audit checklists that verify documentation control by confirming system documentation is version-controlled and accessible, assess record management by confirming the system supports the mandatory five-year retention period for medical records with secure storage and retrieval mechanisms, examine process control by verifying system workflows follow established procedures for data access and user management, and review corrective action procedures by confirming the system supports identification and tracking of issues through audit trails. Department of Health medical information system requirements under Administrative Orders 2012-0012 and 2013-0006 are verified through checklists that confirm data security measures protect patient information through encryption and access controls, verify patient privacy protections prevent unauthorized disclosure, assess interoperability by examining read-only integration with existing CIS modules, review certificate issuance procedures to ensure proper format and release protocols with required physician authentication, and confirm record retention capabilities maintain certificate copies per regulatory requirements.

Data Privacy Act compliance under Republic Act No. 10173 and National Privacy Commission Circular 16-03 employs security and privacy controls evaluation that verifies consent management procedures implement patient consent for data access, confirms access control enforcement through role-based permissions prevents unauthorized access by testing that staff view only permitted data while patients access only their own results and agencies access only assigned worker information, validates encryption protocols secure data at rest through database encryption and data in transit through HTTPS implementation, examines audit trail completeness to confirm documentation of all user login attempts and data access events with tamper-resistant logging, reviews breach notification procedures for incident response, and assesses data retention and disposal policies for alignment with legal requirements. ISO/IEC 25010:2023 software quality characteristics employ systematic quality attribute assessment that measures functional suitability by verifying all planned features work correctly with accurate data retrieval from CIS modules, evaluates performance efficiency through page load time measurements targeting 2-second thresholds and concurrent user load testing, confirms compatibility through verification of integration with existing CIS modules without conflicts, assesses usability through System Usability Scale scores targeting 68 or above (Hyzy et al., 2022), monitors reliability through uptime tracking targeting 99 percent availability, examines security through vulnerability scanning using OWASP ZAP and manual penetration testing, reviews maintainability through code quality assessment, and tests portability by verifying the system operates on different server hardware.

Time-and-motion study methodology adapts Karthikeyan et al. (2024) approach developed for tertiary care hospital outpatient departments, applying the workflow analysis techniques to the secondary clinic context by measuring patient flow through direct observation and recording timestamps at each department transition point to calculate cumulative waiting time and total cycle time. Pre-post quasi-experimental study design validated by Mansoor et al. (2024) assesses operational outcomes before and after system implementation by measuring changes in key performance indicators including completion rates, turnaround times, error frequencies, and staff coordination burden.

The project will not manage or execute financial or billing transactions. While the system may reference billing transaction numbers or payment statuses to verify that examination fees have been processed prior to medical testing, it strictly excludes financial data processing, focusing development resources entirely on operational workflow bottlenecks, clinical data encoding, and result releasing.

Furthermore, while the system requires staff to encode PEME findings directly into the application to facilitate automated collation, it does not alter the medical evaluation protocols or fitness-to-work determination standards established by the clinic. The application serves as a modern digital conduit for these existing clinical standards, ensuring that medical professionals retain complete diagnostic authority while benefiting from automated documentation consolidation.

The project will not include SMS text message alerts to patients and agencies, mobile application development for iOS or Android platforms, advanced analytics and business intelligence dashboards, integration with national health registries or government systems, or telemedicine capabilities. These exclusions prioritize core functionality addressing documented operational problems within available development resources. Advanced features require specialized technical expertise, ongoing maintenance infrastructure, and integration with external communication platforms that exceed the scope of addressing immediate problems of manual status checking and repeated data entry. Email notification functionality is included as it addresses the documented problem of releasing staff having no systematic notification when departments finish their work and agencies having to call or email for status updates, using standard email protocols that can leverage existing clinic email infrastructure currently used for result distribution to agencies.

Testing and evaluation activities are constrained by operational requirements. The clinic cannot suspend patient care services for system testing, cannot allocate extended staff time away from patient care responsibilities, and cannot conduct testing during peak operational periods. Data collection sessions must be scheduled during low-volume periods and kept brief to minimize service impact. This limitation reflects ethical obligations to prioritize patient care over research activities and practical necessity of maintaining clinic revenue and contractual obligations to agency clients. The constraint affects sample sizes for user testing and limits the duration of observation periods but does not prevent collection of valid performance data through focused, carefully scheduled evaluation sessions employing time-and-motion methodology adapted from Karthikeyan et al. (2024) for secondary clinic operations and pre-post quasi-experimental design (Mansoor et al., 2024).

Security assessment will employ open-source vulnerability scanning tools and manual penetration testing following published security testing methodologies. The project will not include professional security audits by certified third-party firms or commercial penetration testing services. This limitation is justified by budget constraints of student capstone projects and represents acceptable risk for a locally-hosted system under existing physical security and network infrastructure controls. Security verification confirms absence of common vulnerabilities documented in established frameworks such as OWASP Top 10 while acknowledging that comprehensive protection against sophisticated attacks requires additional security hardening beyond student project capabilities.

Formal regulatory certification is outside project scope. The system demonstrates compliance readiness through documented controls, implemented security measures, and audit trail capabilities addressing ISO 9001:2015, Department of Health, and Data Privacy Act requirements. However, official certification audits by accredited bodies including ISO certification auditors, Department of Health accreditation teams, or National Privacy Commission assessors require clinic management initiation and involve assessment of broader organizational policies, physical security measures, staff training programs, and administrative procedures beyond information system implementation. The project provides evidence of regulatory compliance through structured verification procedures but does not replace formal certification processes.

### **1.5 Significance of the Study**

For American Hospital Inc., the project addresses documented problems in how the organization monitors ongoing examinations and compiles final results. A functional monitoring and result access system reduces repeated manual checking by aggregating completion status from existing Computer Information System modules, clarifies case status for staff through unified dashboard visualization, shortens the interval between clinical completion and releasing by eliminating idle time when completed results await manual discovery, and automates notification to staff, agencies, and patients when results become available.

For recruitment agencies, the proposed system provides direct access to examination status and results for their workers with automated email notification when results are ready. Agency representatives can verify progress and retrieve completed results without telephone or email coordination.

For individual patients, the proposed system provides visibility into personal examination progress showing which tests have been completed, which remain pending, and what results are available, with email notification when examination results are ready for access. This addresses the current situation where patients must ask staff for updates and have no independent way to track their own status through the multi-department examination process.

For the academic program, the proposed project demonstrates how information systems address specific, documented operational problems in a healthcare setting with real regulatory and operational constraints. The study shows how read-only integration with existing systems can create operational value without disrupting established workflows or requiring additional data entry from clinic staff.

## **Chapter 2**

## **REVIEW OF RELATED LITERATURE AND STUDIES** 

### **2.1 Introduction**

American Hospital Inc. conducts pre-employment medical examinations to determine whether applicants are fit for deployment, yet its PEME operations suffer from fragmented tracking, prolonged waiting times, and delayed result consolidation. To understand how information systems can address these problems, this review synthesizes literature from several domains: healthcare operations management and patient flow optimization, occupational health and PEME service delivery models, queue management and queueing theory in clinical settings, digital health technologies and infrastructure, web-based architectures for operational and patient-facing services, real-time monitoring systems, and data privacy and regulatory compliance in healthcare.

The discussion is organized around three analytic dimensions. The first dimension establishes operational foundations that explain how patient flow, resource allocation, and queue discipline affect waiting times and throughput in outpatient and occupational health settings. The second dimension examines enabling technologies such as hybrid health information environments, web-based portals, dashboards, and local hosting architectures that support real-time visibility and multi-stakeholder access. The third dimension focuses on evaluation methods and quality frameworks, including ISO-aligned quality characteristics, the FURPS plus requirements framework, System Usability Scale benchmarks, time-and-motion analysis, and satisfaction measurements. Together, these strands inform the design of an on-premises, web-based PEME monitoring and result access system that fits the regulatory and operational realities of American Hospital Inc.

### 

### **2.2 Pre-Employment Medical Examination Workflows in Occupational Health**

Pre-employment medical examinations in Philippine occupational health clinics follow standardized protocols set by the Department of Health. These protocols prescribe core tests such as blood work, urinalysis, chest radiography, electrocardiography, and neuro-psychiatric assessment to determine medical fitness for work (DOH Administrative Order No. 2013-0006, n.d.). Clinics must also adapt to client-specific packages that vary by employer, destination country, and position, which adds complexity to scheduling, coordination, and results consolidation. For overseas Filipino workers, the regulatory framework restricts PEME provision to DOH-accredited or DOH-operated clinics while still allowing workers to choose among accredited providers (DOH Administrative Order No. 1, s. 2003, n.d.). Any information system designed for PEME must therefore accommodate standardized protocols and variable employer requirements inside a regulated environment.

The PEME workflow in American Hospital Inc. resembles typical occupational health models, where patients move through multiple departments such as reception, laboratory, radiology, specialty clinics, and releasing. Each department contributes partial results that must be collated into an integrated medical report and fitness-to-work decision. Without real-time tracking, staff rely on repeated manual status checks, phone calls, and physical chart chasing to know where a case is in the process. The literature indicates that in such multi-department workflows, lack of visibility creates idle time, misplaced charts, and failures to meet promised turnaround times (Lima et al., 2024; Samadbeik et al., 2024). A PEME-specific information system must therefore treat each case as a single episode that moves across units, while preserving compliance with DOH accreditation and employer-specific documentation requirements.

#### **2.2.1 PEME Services and Clinical Workflows in the Philippines**

PEME services in the Philippines are specialized examinations that certify applicants as fit, unfit, or fit with restrictions for work, with particular emphasis on overseas employment where medical clearance is a formal prerequisite (DOH Administrative Order No. 1, s. 2003, n.d.). The regulatory framework involves DOH issuances, overseas employment agencies, and international maritime standards for seafarers endorsed by the International Labour Organization (Guidelines on the medical examinations of seafarers, 2011). DOH Administrative Order 2013-0006 classifies PEME facilities into Regular clinics for land-based and domestic seafarers, Special Seafarer clinics for international seafarers, and other specialized types, each with minimum service and equipment standards (DOH Administrative Order No. 2013-0006, n.d.).

Workflows in Philippine PEME clinics include standardized steps such as registration, verification of employer package, physical examination, diagnostic tests, and final medical evaluation, but actual paths can vary based on package composition and clinical findings (DOH Administrative Order No. 2013-0006, n.d.). Studies on healthcare service delivery highlight how multi-stage clinical paths and multi-stakeholder reporting requirements increase coordination demand and heighten the risk of lost time when results are delayed or incomplete (Ezeanyim et al., 2025; Samadbeik et al., 2024). Electronic health record implementations in occupational health contexts have shown potential for improving documentation quality and reducing processing times when integrated into existing clinical workflows (Kowalski-Mcgraw et al., 2023). An information system for American Hospital Inc. must therefore support package-driven routing, multi-stage clearance, and structured result consolidation while remaining consistent with national regulatory frameworks.

#### **2.2.2 Multi-Department Coordination in PEME Operations**

Multi-department PEME operations require coordination across reception, billing, diagnostic units, specialty clinics, and medical directors. Each unit controls a segment of the process but no single actor has a complete real-time view of case status under purely manual systems. DOH regulations define documentation, consent, and record-keeping standards but do not prescribe how information should flow operationally across departments (DOH Administrative Order No. 2013-0006, n.d.). Contemporary operations research emphasizes that lack of a single source of truth for patient status leads to duplicated work, repeated status inquiries, and delays in downstream steps such as physician evaluation or report printing (Lima et al., 2024; Samadbeik et al., 2024; Chen et al., 2024).

Studies of multi-department hospital workflows show that unified tracking mechanisms reduce handoff failures and shorten end-to-end cycle times when they provide each actor with filtered, role-appropriate views of cases in progress (Harbi et al., 2024; Lima et al., 2024). Bottleneck factors in clinical workflows often stem from communication gaps and lack of standardized handoff procedures between departments (Al Moteri et al., 2024). Queue-aware scheduling and inter-department coordination depend on accurate, timely updates for each step completed, rather than retrospective reconciliation of paper forms (Zamani et al., 2024). Health information systems that centralize patient tracking across multiple service points have demonstrated improvements in care coordination and reductions in patient waiting times (Chen et al., 2024). For American Hospital Inc., this implies that a PEME monitoring system must centralize status updates for all departments, allow controlled editing only at appropriate stages, and expose real-time views of queues and backlogs to staff managing daily operations.

#### **2.2.3 Overseas Filipino Worker Medical Assessment Requirements**

PEME for overseas Filipino workers is tied to deployment decisions and international compliance. DOH guidelines specify mandatory examination elements for seafarers and land-based workers, and align with maritime and labor conventions that require standardized documentation formats and validity periods (DOH Administrative Order No. 2013-0006, n.d.; Guidelines on the medical examinations of seafarers, 2011). Clinics must produce certificates acceptable to foreign principals and flag states, and are subject to audits that verify adherence to DOH standards and international guidelines. Failure to maintain complete, accurate, and timely records can lead to sanctions and loss of accreditation (Licensing/Accreditation of Health Facilities and Services, n.d.).

Because OFW examinations are often linked to fixed departure dates, delays in any part of the workflow can lead to missed vessels or flight schedules. The literature emphasizes that for healthcare services with time-sensitive outcomes, alignment between clinical processes, documentation, and external timetables is critical (Zamani et al., 2025; Youn et al., 2022). Visibility into examination progress and result status is important for employment agencies that coordinate placements (Kowalski-Mcgraw et al., 2023). A web-based monitoring and results access system that allows agencies to see PEME status and summary fitness decisions in a controlled way can reduce repeated inquiries and help agencies schedule applicants more efficiently, provided that access is limited to necessary information and is consistent with data privacy requirements (Republic Act 10173, n.d.).

#### **2.2.4 Rush Processing and Priority Queue Management in Time-Critical Medical Services**

Rush or expedited PEME cases introduce additional operational pressure because examinations and result consolidation must be completed within compressed timeframes. Research on time-critical clinical services shows that unstructured handling of urgent cases can disrupt routine workflows, prolong average waiting times, and create inequities in access when no priority rules guide resource allocation (Harbi et al., 2024; Alipour-Vaezi et al., 2022). Studies of emergency and urgent care units demonstrate that explicit priority disciplines and differentiated queues for urgent and routine cases can reduce service time variability and improve completion of high-priority cases without fully displacing routine clients (Wang et al., 2025; Liao et al., 2022).

Priority-based queue discipline separates patients into service classes so that time-critical cases are prioritized while routine cases still meet agreed performance thresholds. Multi-tier queueing models allocate more capacity to rush cases while preserving minimum capacity for regular cases and are often guided by service level agreements that specify acceptable completion percentages within defined time limits (Adhicandra et al., 2024; Liu et al., 2024). Research on queue management systems indicates that when priority rules and capacity allocations are implemented and monitored through digital systems, urgent completion metrics improve and routine throughput remains acceptable (AlQudah et al., 2024; Hassan et al., 2022). Empirical work on appointment and scheduling systems shows that priority-aware resource allocation can balance competing demands without creating excessive delays for lower-priority patients (Manarte, 2024). For American Hospital Inc., the literature supports explicit representation of rush versus regular PEME queues in the monitoring system, including dedicated indicators and configurable service targets for each class.

### **2.3 Healthcare Operations Management and Patient Flow Optimization**

Healthcare operations management coordinates processes, resources, and workflows to achieve efficiency, quality, and patient satisfaction (Harbi et al., 2024). It includes patient throughput optimization, capacity planning, resource allocation, and continuous quality improvement strategies that can be applied to outpatient and occupational health settings (Harrison et al., 2025; Zhao et al., 2025). For PEME clinics, these principles provide a framework for redesigning multi-department workflows so that scarce resources such as diagnostic equipment, physicians, and administrative staff are used more effectively and end-to-end examination times are reduced.

Operations management literature emphasizes that patient flow is a system-level phenomenon shaped not only by individual tasks but also by bottlenecks, variability in arrivals, and coordination across departments. Studies of outpatient clinics show that unbalanced workload distribution, unclear routing rules, and limited shared visibility into queues often lead to prolonged waiting times and incomplete visits (Harbi et al., 2024; Harrison et al., 2025). For American Hospital Inc., the same concepts apply to PEME cycles that involve serial and parallel processes. To improve performance, the system must not only automate documentation but also expose how cases move through the process so that managers can identify delays and adjust resource deployment in line with operations management best practices.

#### **2.3.1 Fundamentals of Healthcare Operations Management**

Fundamental models of healthcare operations management conceptualize care delivery as a network of interdependent processes that transform inputs such as patients and resources into outputs such as completed consultations, diagnostic reports, and clinical decisions (Harbi et al., 2024; Javaid et al., 2024). Key levers include scheduling, capacity allocation, process standardization, and performance measurement. Research indicates that clinics that systematically monitor throughput and apply structured improvement methods achieve better service times and higher patient satisfaction than clinics that rely on ad hoc adjustments (Zamani et al., 2025; Ferreira et al., 2023).

More recent work extends these principles to occupational health and pre-employment settings, where the output is often a fitness-to-work certificate under time constraints set by employers or deployment schedules. These studies highlight the need to integrate information about patient arrivals, resource availability, and examination requirements to coordinate tasks efficiently (Harbi et al., 2024; Machireddy, 2023). Resource planning strategies in healthcare emphasize that operational efficiency depends on matching capacity with demand patterns, which requires accurate data collection and real-time monitoring capabilities (Fattahi et al., 2023). In American Hospital Inc., adopting this view means treating PEME not as isolated departmental tasks but as a coordinated operations system that can be monitored and controlled through a dedicated information system.

#### **2.3.2 Patient Flow and Throughput Metrics in Outpatient Settings**

Patient flow literature defines flow as the progression of patients through a series of stages, from registration and triage to diagnostics and discharge, and uses throughput metrics such as waiting time, length of stay, and completion rates to quantify performance (Samadbeik et al., 2024; Samadbeik et al., 2025). Studies show that small delays at early stages can cascade into large end-to-end delays, especially in systems with multiple serial dependencies (Zamani et al., 2025). Patient flow analysis with real-time tracking has demonstrated effectiveness in optimizing consultation visits and reducing unnecessary waiting periods (Mesko et al., 2022).

Research in outpatient clinics and diagnostic centers indicates that measuring and visualizing throughput metrics is a prerequisite for improvement. Any intervention aimed at reducing waiting times or improving completion rates must be evaluated against baseline measures and monitored through feedback loops (Samadbeik et al., 2024; Samadbeik et al., 2025; Zamani et al., 2025). Studies on patient satisfaction consistently show that waiting time is among the strongest predictors of overall satisfaction with healthcare services (Bhatt et al., 2024; Leow & Liew, 2022). Optimization of outpatient waiting times has been linked to improvements in national quality indicators, demonstrating the strategic importance of flow management (Prayudi et al., 2024). For American Hospital Inc., the PEME monitoring system will need to capture timestamps at key steps, such as registration, departmental arrival and completion, and result release, so that patient flow can be quantified and adjusted according to these established metrics.

#### **2.3.3 Queue Theory and Waiting Time Reduction Models**

Queueing theory provides mathematical models to analyze waiting line systems and to study how arrival rates, service times, and capacity decisions influence waiting times and system congestion. Work in healthcare queueing shows that balancing arrival patterns and service capacity through appropriate scheduling and resource pooling can significantly reduce average waiting times without necessarily increasing resources (Alipour-Vaezi et al., 2022; Aminah et al., 2025). Queueing theory is consistently described as a core framework for understanding and addressing waiting time problems in healthcare settings, with recent reviews and applications highlighting its role in modelling hospital queues and optimizing service performance (Suleiman et al., 2022; Sachidhanandham & Srinivasan, 2025; Okemmiri et al., 2024\)

Simulation models and analytical formulations have been used to evaluate alternative appointment rules, triage schemes, and routing policies in outpatient settings (Aminah et al., 2025; Okemmiri et al., 2024). Mathematical programming approaches have been applied to analyze and improve robust queue management in healthcare systems, demonstrating the potential for quantitative methods to guide operational decisions (Ahmed, 2025). Single-server and multi-server exponential queueing models have been applied in hospital contexts to optimize resource utilization and reduce patient waiting times (Suleiman et al., 2022). Recent studies also explore how digital tools can support the implementation of queueing-theory-informed policies. These studies show that systems that dynamically display current load and waiting times support better decision-making for staff and reduce perceived waiting times among patients (Liang & He, 2023; AlQudah et al., 2024). Although American Hospital Inc. will not implement advanced optimization algorithms in the initial capstone phase, the literature supports using queueing concepts to inform the design of status indicators, departmental load dashboards, and simple priority rules inside the PEME monitoring system.

#### **2.3.4 Process Bottleneck Identification and Flow Analysis**

Bottleneck analysis locates stages in a process where capacity constraints or variability cause queues and delays. In healthcare, studies show that bottlenecks often arise at diagnostic units, physician consultations, or administrative release steps, and that system-wide improvements require rebalancing these constraints rather than optimizing individual steps in isolation (Al Moteri et al., 2024; Lima et al., 2024). Bottleneck factors impacting clinical workflows include communication gaps, documentation requirements, and resource limitations that create cumulative delays across service points (Al Moteri et al., 2024).

For pre-employment clinics, flow analysis methods such as process mapping, time-and-motion measurements, and throughput tracking have been used to identify where patients spend most of their time and which handoffs are prone to error. These methods inform targeted interventions such as real-time alerting when cases linger in a stage beyond a tolerated threshold or when queues in a department reach a predefined limit (Lima et al., 2024; Benjamin, 2024). Hospital operations management research emphasizes the importance of characterizing patient process flows to identify inefficiencies and guide improvement efforts (Lima et al., 2024). Studies of emergency nursing workflows have shown that patient flow management requires continuous situational awareness and proactive intervention to prevent queue buildup (Benjamin, 2024). The PEME monitoring system for American Hospital Inc. is designed in line with these findings, with process diagrams and monitoring views that make bottlenecks visible so that staff can intervene early.

### 

### **2.4 Queue Management Systems and Real-Time Patient Monitoring**

Queue management systems support patient registration, ticketing, routing, and calling across service points. In healthcare settings, these systems range from simple manual approaches such as physical numbering and verbal calling to advanced digital platforms with integrated kiosks, displays, and electronic queues (Adhicandra et al., 2024; Hassan et al., 2022). Real-time patient monitoring extends basic queuing by providing continuous visibility into where each patient is in the workflow and by offering dashboards that show departmental load and potential bottlenecks (Sekarini et al., 2025; Liang & He, 2023; Munbodh et al., 2022).

In environments like American Hospital Inc., which already maintains clinical information systems and paper records, the challenge is not only to modernize queues but also to respect regulatory constraints and the existing hybrid processes. The literature indicates that incremental introduction of digital queue and monitoring systems, anchored on real-time displays and status updates, can improve patient flow and staff coordination even when full electronic health record adoption is not feasible (Adhicandra et al., 2024; AlQudah et al., 2024). Studies on queue management system acceptance in healthcare emphasize that perceived usefulness, ease of use, and compatibility with existing workflows are critical factors for successful implementation (AlQudah et al., 2024).

#### **2.4.1 Types and Evolution of Queue Management Systems in Healthcare**

Queue management systems have evolved from manual queues to semi-automated systems with LED counters and kiosks, and more recently to fully integrated platforms linked to electronic records. Studies from outpatient clinics and diagnostic centers show that shifting from manual to digital queues reduces confusion about service order, lowers perceived unfairness, and improves waiting room organization (Hassan et al., 2022; Baballe, 2022). Research on hospital queue management systems indicates that digital implementations have positive effects on patient satisfaction and operational efficiency when properly designed and implemented (Baballe, 2022).

In many low- and middle-income settings, however, clinics still rely on paper logbooks and verbal calling, which are prone to errors when patient volumes grow. Evidence shows that even basic digital ticketing combined with structured calling can reduce miscalls and lost charts (Hassan et al., 2022; Nabila & Ayuningtyas, 2024). Web-based reservation systems have demonstrated effectiveness in reducing outpatient waiting times by allowing patients to schedule appointments and receive queue numbers remotely (Nabila & Ayuningtyas, 2024). For American Hospital Inc., the proposed PEME system does not aim to replicate all features of advanced commercial products but draws from this evolution to implement role-appropriate digital queues and views that work with existing reception and departmental processes.

#### **2.4.2 Real-Time Patient Flow Visibility and Routing Dashboards**

Real-time visibility tools and routing dashboards display current queues, service status, and key performance indicators in a way that supports operational decision-making. Studies demonstrate that such dashboards help staff identify congestion before it leads to severe delays and support rerouting or rescheduling when capacity constraints arise (Liang & He, 2023; Sekarini et al., 2025; Munbodh et al., 2022). Research on real-time operational dashboards has shown that continuous displays of patient flow metrics enable proactive management and improve overall department performance by driving agile decision-making across health systems (Liang & He, 2023; Mesko et al., 2022).

Research also shows that providing staff with a shared overview of patient queues increases accountability and reduces the tendency to attend only to local queues without regard to global performance (Liang & He, 2023; Sekarini et al., 2025). Dashboard applications for monitoring patient data in hospitals have been shown to improve coordination by presenting consolidated views of patient status across multiple service points (Sekarini et al., 2025). Real-time analysis and display of quantitative measures has demonstrated effectiveness in tracking and improving clinical workflow performance (Munbodh et al., 2022). When combined with simple rules such as maximum tolerated waiting time per stage, dashboards can trigger early interventions and cross-department coordination (Harbi et al., 2024). For American Hospital Inc., the PEME dashboard is designed to give reception, nursing, and departmental heads a consolidated view of cases in progress and waiting counts per unit so that they can prioritize, communicate, and adjust assignments in line with best practices in real-time patient flow monitoring.

#### **2.4.3 Department Load Monitoring and Bottleneck Prevention**

Department load monitoring focuses on the distribution of work across units and on the identification of overloaded services that may become bottlenecks. Studies show that when dashboards show both current load and historical patterns, managers can adjust staffing, redistribute tasks, or redirect patients to alternative units to prevent sustained congestion (Al Moteri et al., 2024; Shoaib et al., 2023). Multi-tier healthcare facility network simulations have demonstrated that capacity planning informed by real-time load data can improve resource utilization and reduce patient waiting times (Shoaib et al., 2023).

In environments where resources are fixed, early detection of overload through monitoring helps prevent queue growth and protects downstream departments from cascading delays. Research on bottleneck factors in nursing workflows shows that systematic identification and prioritization of improvement efforts can reduce workflow disruptions and improve patient care delivery (Al Moteri et al., 2024). Patient-centered outpatient process optimization systems based on intelligent guidance have demonstrated improvements in patient flow by directing patients to less congested service points (Wang et al., 2025). For American Hospital Inc., PEME cases pass through diagnostic and clinical departments whose capacity is shared with other patient types. Literature on load monitoring suggests that visual indicators such as color-coded thresholds for queue length or waiting time help staff recognize when a unit is approaching problematic levels (Sekarini et al., 2025; Liang & He, 2023; Munbodh et al., 2022). Incorporating these indicators into the PEME dashboard allows staff to adjust schedules or coordinate with departments before bottlenecks crystallize into missed service commitments.

#### **2.4.4 Priority-Based Queue Discipline in Healthcare Settings**

Priority-based queue discipline assigns different levels of urgency to patient groups and allocates capacity accordingly. Research on outpatient and diagnostic services shows that priority rules, when clearly defined and implemented, can improve completion times for urgent cases while still maintaining acceptable service for routine patients (Adhicandra et al., 2024; Alipour-Vaezi et al., 2022). Optimization of hospital queue management using priority queue algorithms has demonstrated effectiveness in emergency service prioritization without severely impacting routine patient flow (Adhicandra et al., 2024).

Allowing urgent cases to pre-empt routine appointments and reassigning routine slots when necessary can reduce blocking probabilities and forced cancellations. Studies on strategic queueing behavior of different patient groups in healthcare systems show that explicit priority rules help manage competing demands and reduce overall system congestion (Liu et al., 2024). Markov decision optimization models for medical service resources have demonstrated that two-class patient queue systems can effectively balance urgent and routine cases through appropriate capacity allocation (Wang et al., 2025). Research on data-driven decision-making methodologies for emergency department queueing has shown that prioritization frameworks improve resource utilization and patient outcomes (Alipour-Vaezi et al., 2022).

In PEME settings, rush clients who have imminent deployment deadlines represent a natural high-priority class. The literature supports the design of distinct priority classes with explicit service level targets and transparent visibility in the queue system. For American Hospital Inc., this means that the PEME monitoring system must distinguish rush and regular cases in its views and reports, provide predictable handling rules, and allow managers to verify that rush service commitments are met without unintentionally delaying regular clients beyond acceptable limits.

#### **2.4.5 Automated Notification Systems in Healthcare Workflow Coordination**

Automated notification systems in healthcare enable timely communication of status changes, task completions, and alerts to relevant stakeholders without requiring manual intervention. Research on clinical information systems shows that automated alerts and notifications can reduce communication delays, improve care coordination, and decrease the administrative burden on staff who would otherwise need to make phone calls or send manual updates (Kang et al., 2024; Chen et al., 2024). Early warning systems with automated notification capabilities have demonstrated effectiveness in acute care settings by alerting staff to critical status changes that require immediate attention (Kang et al., 2024).

Studies on digital information ecosystems in healthcare emphasize that automated notifications support care coordination by ensuring that relevant parties receive timely updates about patient progress and task completions (Chen et al., 2024). In outpatient and diagnostic settings, automated notifications can inform patients when results are ready, alert staff when cases require attention, and notify external stakeholders when processing milestones are reached (Steitz et al., 2023; Hulter et al., 2023; Petrovskaya et al., 2023). Research on patient perspectives regarding immediate access to test results through online portals shows that automated notification of result availability improves patient satisfaction and engagement (Steitz et al., 2023; Bruno et al., 2022).

Email-based notification systems offer advantages in healthcare workflow coordination because they can leverage existing infrastructure, provide documentation of communications, and reach recipients across different locations and devices (Stoumpos et al., 2023). Studies on digital transformation in healthcare indicate that email notifications integrated with information systems can reduce the volume of status inquiry calls and improve coordination between healthcare facilities and external stakeholders (Stoumpos et al., 2023; Javaid et al., 2024). For American Hospital Inc., the PEME monitoring system includes automated email notification functionality that alerts releasing staff when all department results are complete, notifies agency representatives when their workers examination results become available, and informs individual patients when their results are ready for access. This design addresses the documented problem of releasing staff having no systematic notification when departments finish their work and agencies having to call or email repeatedly for status updates.

### **2.5 Hybrid Health Information Environments, Regulatory Compliance, and Quality Management**

Hybrid information systems seek to combine digital efficiency with regulatory requirements for paper documentation by designing workflows that support multimodal data capture and processing while preserving consistency and auditability (Cronin et al., 2025). These systems face challenges such as manual data entry inefficiencies, risk of data inaccuracy or loss, and increased staff workload when paper records must still be retained for regulatory compliance (Cronin et al., 2025). Nevertheless, electronic medical record implementations have shown substantial benefits including reductions in documentation time and improvements in documentation quality when supported by appropriate infrastructure, training, and compliance measures (Torab-Miandoab et al., 2025).

For occupational health PEME clinics, understanding hybrid system design is therefore critical to maintaining mandated paper records while realizing digital operational improvements and ensuring that electronic tools complement rather than replace medico-legal paper documentation, as required in settings such as American Hospital Inc. The Philippine healthcare context presents particular challenges and opportunities for hybrid systems given the persistence of paper-based processes alongside partial computerization in many facilities (Amor C. Tinam-isan & F. Naga, 2024; Bettina D. Evio et al., 2024).

#### **2.5.1 Hybrid Paper-Digital Health Information Systems**

Many healthcare facilities operate in hybrid environments where electronic systems coexist with paper records. Studies describe hybrid setups as pragmatic responses to regulatory and medico-legal requirements, infrastructure constraints, and change management challenges (Cronin et al., 2025; Hospodkowski & Caithamlov, 2025). While hybrid systems can preserve existing documentation practices, they often create duplication, reconciliation tasks, and risks of data inconsistency when electronic and paper records diverge.

Hospital and clinic case studies show that hybrid documentation frequently requires staff to transcribe data from paper to digital systems or vice versa, which increases workload and error risk (Cronin et al., 2025; Torab-Miandoab et al., 2025). However, when electronic layers are designed as operational tracking tools on top of legally mandated paper records, they can still improve visibility and coordination without replacing medico-legal charts. A qualitative study of hybrid health management information systems in a Tanzanian healthcare context documented staff experiences with the challenges and opportunities of balancing digital and paper processes (Cronin et al., 2025). Research on hybrid management in healthcare from Czech hospitals revealed lessons learned about coordinating paper and digital information flows to maintain regulatory compliance while improving operational efficiency (Hospodkowski & Caithamlov, 2025).

This perspective is directly relevant to American Hospital Inc., where the existing clinical information system and paper records remain the official medical record, while the proposed PEME system provides an operational status layer that centralizes tracking, queue information, and summary results. The PEME monitoring system reads data from the existing CIS without modifying clinical records, thereby preserving the paper records as the medico-legal source of truth while enabling real-time operational visibility.

#### **2.5.2 Health Data Privacy and Security in the Philippine Context**

The Data Privacy Act of 2012 and its implementing rules treat health information as sensitive personal data and impose strict requirements on collection, processing, storage, and disclosure (Republic Act 10173, n.d.). Clinics must implement reasonable organizational, physical, and technical measures, enforce purpose limitation and data minimization, and respect data subject rights. Studies on privacy governance in healthcare show that systems that centralize monitoring and result access must incorporate access control, audit logs, and limited data views to protect confidentiality (Ibrahim et al., 2024; Fareed & Yassin, 2022).

Role-based access control is a critical security mechanism for healthcare information systems that store sensitive patient data. Research demonstrates that RBAC schemes with trust mechanisms can effectively prevent unauthorized access while enabling authorized users to access only the information necessary for their roles (Fareed & Yassin, 2022; Butt et al., 2023). Security risk assessments of patient portals in hospital systems have identified common vulnerabilities and recommended controls including strong authentication, role-based permissions, and audit logging (Yeh et al., 2024).

DOH and licensing bodies also enforce record retention rules. Administrative issuances require that paper records be kept for a minimum of five years in designated storage areas, even when electronic systems are in place (Bush, n.d.). Research on compliance in hybrid setups highlights that digital systems must be designed to complement rather than replace mandated paper records, and that digital views for external stakeholders should expose only the minimum necessary information for their role (Petrovskaya et al., 2023; Ibrahim et al., 2024). Multi-factor authentication in healthcare information systems has been shown to enhance security while maintaining usability when appropriately designed (Suleski et al., 2023; Fareed & Yassin, 2022).

For American Hospital Inc., this implies that the PEME system must limit external portal views to status and summary fitness information, maintain paper records as medico-legal documents, and support retention and access controls consistent with national data privacy and health regulations. Implementation of role-based access control ensures that staff view only permitted data while patients access only their own results and agencies access only assigned worker information.

#### **2.5.3 Department of Health Medical Information System Requirements**

The Department of Health establishes requirements for medical information systems serving occupational health and PEME clinics through Administrative Orders including DOH AO 2012-0012 and DOH AO 2013-0006 (DOH Administrative Order No. 2013-0006, n.d.). These orders specify that PEME facilities must maintain proper documentation of medical findings, ensure secure storage of patient records, and follow prescribed procedures for certificate issuance and record retention. The orders establish regulatory standards for data security, patient privacy protections, interoperability requirements, and certificate authentication procedures.

Electronic health records and occupational data systems must support interoperability with diverse data sources while maintaining data integrity and auditability (Kowalski-Mcgraw et al., 2023). Occupational health information systems designed for compliance with regulatory requirements must incorporate mechanisms for documenting system access, recording data modifications, and maintaining audit trails that demonstrate compliance with DOH standards (Jedwab et al., 2022). Implementation of quality management systems according to ISO 9001:2015 standards in healthcare contexts has included provisions for proper documentation control and record management that align with DOH requirements (Avruscio et al., 2022; Mercader Alarcon et al., 2023).

For American Hospital Inc., compliance with DOH requirements means that the PEME monitoring system must support proper documentation practices, provide secure storage and retrieval mechanisms for medical records, enable verification of physician authentication on fitness-to-work determinations, and maintain certificates and supporting documentation per regulatory requirements. The system design incorporates audit trails that document all user access and data modifications to demonstrate compliance readiness.

#### **2.5.4 ISO 9001:2015 Quality Management in Healthcare Information Systems**

ISO 9001:2015 defines quality management system principles around customer focus, leadership, process orientation, evidence-based decision-making, and continuous improvement. Healthcare organizations that adopt ISO 9001 often operationalize these principles through defined procedures, documented processes, and systematic monitoring of performance indicators such as timeliness, error rates, and service reliability (Bugdol, 2024; Petryk et al., 2023). Implementation of ISO 9001:2015 in healthcare settings has produced documented improvements in process control, error reduction, and operational consistency (Avruscio et al., 2022; Mercader Alarcon et al., 2023).

Research shows that information systems can support ISO 9001 implementation by standardizing workflows, generating audit trails, and providing data for corrective and preventive actions (Bugdol, 2024; Hartika et al., n.d.). Quality management strategies in healthcare organizations emphasize the importance of systematic process monitoring and continuous improvement based on objective performance data (Petryk et al., 2023). Analysis of ISO 9001:2015 implementation in hospitals has revealed that effective quality management systems require documented procedures, staff training, and regular review of performance metrics (Hartika et al., n.d.).

For PEME operations at American Hospital Inc., an on-premises web-based system that captures process steps, timestamps, and error incidents can become a key component of the quality management system. It can provide objective data to evaluate whether patient flow and turnaround commitments are met and supply evidence for internal and external audits. The monitoring system supports ISO 9001 compliance by maintaining version-controlled documentation, recording all examination process steps with timestamps, tracking error incidents through audit trails, and enabling corrective action procedures that address identified quality issues. These capabilities align with ISO 9001:2015 principles and provide evidence of systematic quality management that benefits both the organization and its stakeholders.

### **2.6 Web-Based Patient Portals and External Result Access**

Web-based portals extend clinical information systems to patients and external stakeholders by providing online access to selected health information, appointment details, and educational resources. Studies show that portals can enhance transparency, patient engagement, and satisfaction when designed with appropriate usability and privacy safeguards (Alomar et al., 2024; Lear et al., 2022). At the same time, literature warns that poorly controlled portals risk exposing sensitive data and increasing administrative burdens if patients rely on staff to troubleshoot portal access issues.

In the context of PEME, portals for patients and client companies are primarily used for status checking and access to fitness certificates rather than full clinical histories. The literature supports a role-based view where staff have detailed access to operational and clinical data, while external users see limited information tailored to their decisions, such as whether a case is complete and whether the applicant is fit for deployment (Alomar et al., 2024; Jawad et al., 2024). This distinction underpins the design of the American Hospital Inc. PEME portal, which should expose examination status and summary decisions without revealing more information than necessary.

#### **2.6.1 Patient Portal Design and Security Considerations**

Research on patient portals highlights several design principles: clear navigation, simple language, accessible layout, and strong authentication and authorization controls. Security studies emphasize the need for role-based access control, encryption, and audit logging, together with practices that protect login credentials and limit access from shared devices (Islam et al., 2025; Mathieu et al., 2025; Suleski et al., 2023).

Patient-facing systems must also address digital literacy and device access. Studies report that non-intuitive designs, complex passwords, and lack of clear feedback discourage portal use even when features are available (Islam et al., 2025; Suleski et al., 2023). For American Hospital Inc., the PEME patient portal should use straightforward flows for credential creation, login, and case lookup, and should protect accounts through reasonable security without making access overly burdensome. Authentication and authorization must be designed so that only the patient, or a duly authorized representative, can see PEME status and summary results.

#### **2.6.2 Result Delivery and Patient Engagement through Portals**

Studies in hospitals and clinics show that portals can accelerate delivery of laboratory results and reports, improve patients’ understanding of their health, and reduce the need for phone calls and in-person visits for simple inquiries (Mathieu et al., 2025; Swart & Michell, 2025; van der Mee et al., 2024). When patients can see completion status and result availability online, they report higher satisfaction and a greater sense of control over their care trajectory.

At the same time, some research notes that unmediated release of complex clinical results can cause anxiety or confusion, especially when technical terms are not explained (Mathieu et al., 2025; Swart & Michell, 2025). For PEME, where the main concern is fitness for work rather than chronic disease management, literature supports sharing clear summary statuses such as fit, fit with restrictions, or unfit, combined with simple indications of whether all required tests are complete. This level of detail can reduce repeated status calls and encourage patients to plan their next steps, while clinical details remain available to staff for consultations when needed.

#### **2.6.3 External Stakeholder Access: Client Companies and Manning Agencies**

Client companies and manning agencies are central stakeholders in PEME, since they schedule applicants, coordinate documentation, and make deployment decisions. Research on occupational health portals notes that employers benefit from timely visibility into examination completion and fitness outcomes for their applicants, but that access must be limited to information needed for employment decisions and must respect workers’ privacy rights (Mathieu et al., 2025).

For American Hospital Inc., the literature suggests providing agency and employer users with controlled portal accounts where they can view lists of applicants linked to their organization, see status indicators such as scheduled, in progress, pending review, or completed, and access summary fitness decisions once results are finalized. Access to detailed clinical data remains restricted. This approach aligns with data minimization and supports agencies in planning deployment while reducing the volume of phone calls and emails requesting status updates.

### **2.7 Digital Health Technologies and Healthcare Information System Architecture**

Digital health technologies support clinical and administrative processes by integrating data, automating workflows, and enabling new forms of communication and monitoring. In many facilities, these technologies are implemented as modular systems that combine core clinical applications with supporting tools such as dashboards, portals, and specialized registries. The choice of architecture influences scalability, reliability, regulatory compliance, and total cost of ownership. For American Hospital Inc., the literature supports an on-premises web-based approach where a three-tier architecture separates the presentation layer, application logic, and database. This structure allows the PEME monitoring and portal system to integrate with existing clinical information systems through controlled interfaces while keeping data under local control and satisfying national data privacy and licensing requirements.

#### **2.7.1 Web-Based Healthcare Information Systems: Architecture and Deployment Models**

Web-based healthcare information systems typically adopt client-server or three-tier architectures in which browsers access application servers that mediate requests to a database. Studies report that such architectures simplify deployment and updates, because functionality is centralized on the server and accessed through standard web technologies (Perdana & Mokhtar, 2023; Lindsay & Lytle, 2022). In contrast, thick-client and distributed desktop systems require installation and maintenance on many endpoints.

The literature compares on-premises, cloud-based, and hybrid hosting models. Cloud systems offer scalability and reduced infrastructure management but raise concerns about data sovereignty, compliance with local regulations, and reliance on external vendors, especially for sensitive health data (Chung et al., 2025; Raunaq et al., 2025). On-premises systems provide full data control and may align better with strict local regulations, though they demand internal capacity for maintenance and backup (Stoumpos et al., 2023). Research on health informatics has documented diverse architectural approaches and their implications for different healthcare contexts (Javaid et al., 2024). Studies on leveraging digital technologies for healthcare transformation indicate that architecture decisions must balance functionality, compliance, scalability, and cost considerations (Perdana & Mokhtar, 2023).

For American Hospital Inc., an on-premises web-based architecture is consistent with privacy and licensing requirements and supports integration with existing local clinical systems. This approach allows the facility to maintain control over sensitive patient data, implement local security policies, and ensure compliance with Philippine data privacy regulations without dependency on external cloud providers.

#### **2.7.2 Read-Only Integration and Data Aggregation from Legacy Systems**

A critical design consideration for the PEME monitoring system is read-only integration with the existing clinical information system. This approach allows the new system to access data from existing CIS modules without modifying, deleting, or writing to the original clinical records. Read-only integration protects the integrity of existing clinical data, avoids disruption to established workflows, and eliminates risks of corrupting data that staff depend on for patient care.

Electronic health record interoperability and occupational data integration present technical and organizational challenges that read-only integration strategies can help address (Kowalski-Mcgraw et al., 2023). Data aggregation from multiple clinical sources requires careful design to ensure consistency and accuracy of aggregated information. Real-time data aggregation can create performance challenges if the existing CIS is heavily loaded or if query performance is poor. Literature on health information ecosystem design emphasizes that data integration must be planned carefully to avoid disrupting existing systems while enabling new capabilities (Chen et al., 2024).

For American Hospital Inc., read-only access means that the PEME monitoring system retrieves admission data, package information, laboratory results, radiology findings, ECG recordings, psychology evaluations, and other clinical data from the existing CIS but does not write back or modify that data. The system aggregates this information to determine case status, identify which examinations are complete, and track which remain pending. This design preserves the existing CIS as the system of record for clinical data while enabling the new monitoring system to provide operational visibility without introducing data consistency risks.

#### **2.7.3 Local Hosting and Security in Philippine Healthcare Settings**

Studies on health information systems in low- and middle-income countries highlight that local hosting is often chosen to comply with national data privacy regulations and to maintain operational continuity in the face of variable internet connectivity (Amor C. Tinam-isan & F. Naga, 2024; Chung et al., 2025). Local servers allow facilities to implement physical and network controls in their own premises, such as restricted server rooms, firewalls, and local backup procedures. The Data Privacy Act of 2012 places obligations on data controllers to implement reasonable security measures, which local hosting supports by keeping sensitive health information within the facility.

Security literature emphasizes that even on-premises systems must implement defense-in-depth measures. These include authentication and authorization mechanisms, encryption in transit on internal networks, secure database configuration, and regular monitoring of access logs and system events (Benaich et al., 2024; Suleski et al., 2023). Implementation of secure multi-factor authentication protocols in healthcare cloud and SDN environments demonstrates that security controls can be adapted across different hosting models (M Abd El-Aziz et al., 2022). Research on security risk assessment for patient portals identifies common vulnerabilities and recommends controls including strong authentication, encryption, audit logging, and regular security testing (Yeh et al., 2024).

For American Hospital Inc., where the PEME monitoring system will co-exist with other local systems, design decisions must ensure that the new system respects existing security policies and that integration does not introduce new vulnerabilities. Local hosting allows the facility to maintain physical control over servers, implement local network security measures, and ensure that patient data remains within the facility premises in compliance with Philippine data privacy principles.

#### **2.7.4 User Interface Design for Healthcare Dashboards and Real-Time Monitoring**

User interface design strongly influences whether healthcare workers can effectively use dashboards and monitoring systems. Studies show that dashboards that display too much information or that rely on cluttered layouts reduce usability and hinder decision-making, while clear layouts with grouped information, suitable font sizes, and simple visual encodings are associated with better task performance (Almasi et al., 2023; Khanbhai et al., 2022). Usability evaluation of dashboards through systematic literature review has identified design principles and tools that support effective dashboard implementation in healthcare settings (Almasi et al., 2023).

Real-time monitoring interfaces should support quick visual scanning to assess status, rather than require users to read long tables or navigate multiple screens. Research recommends using simple visual indicators such as traffic-light colors, icons, and concise labels to signal status and threshold breaches, together with consistent interaction patterns for filtering and drill-down (Khanbhai et al., 2022; Almasi et al., 2023; Sekarini et al., 2025). Enriching patient experience feedback through web-based dashboard development using co-design and heuristic evaluation has demonstrated that user-centered design approaches improve dashboard effectiveness and adoption (Khanbhai et al., 2022). Usability and evaluation research on health information systems in emergency departments shows that mixed-methods approaches combining usability testing with qualitative feedback improve system design (Østervang et al., 2024).

For the American Hospital Inc. PEME dashboard, these principles imply consolidated views that show current queue lengths, departmental loads, and status categories per case in a single page, with options to filter by package, department, or priority. Detailed information is available on secondary screens so that the main dashboard remains focused on situational awareness and quick decision support. Visual indicators using color coding, clear labels, and simple icons should help staff quickly recognize normal operations versus situations requiring attention or intervention.
