### **2.8 System Usability and Evaluation Methodologies for Healthcare IT**

Evaluation of healthcare information systems must address both technical quality and user experience. Literature emphasizes that systems that perform well technically but are difficult to use or that do not fit existing workflows are unlikely to be adopted or to deliver expected benefits (Hyzy et al., 2022; Dehghani Mahmoodabadi et al., 2025). As a result, many studies combine usability evaluation, operational performance measurement, and user satisfaction assessment when assessing digital interventions in clinical settings (Nadav et al., 2024).

For American Hospital Inc., the evaluation of the PEME monitoring and result access system is grounded in several complementary frameworks and methods. Requirements are organized using the FURPS plus structure, which groups functional, usability, reliability, performance, and supportability requirements, and technical quality is viewed through the lens of ISO-aligned characteristics such as functional suitability, performance efficiency, usability, reliability, and security. Usability is assessed through standardized instruments, while operational impact is evaluated using time-based metrics and before-and-after comparisons that follow accepted quasi-experimental designs (Hyzy et al., 2022; Dehghani Mahmoodabadi et al., 2025; Mansoor et al., 2024).

#### **2.8.1 System Usability Scale and Healthcare IT Benchmarks**

The System Usability Scale is a ten-item questionnaire that produces a single usability score from zero to one hundred. It has been widely used across healthcare information systems, including electronic health records, clinical decision support tools, patient portals, and mobile health applications (Hyzy et al., 2022). Meta-analytic work suggests that an average SUS score of about sixty-eight represents acceptable usability, with scores in the seventies and above indicating good usability and higher likelihood of user acceptance (Hyzy et al., 2022).

Healthcare IT benchmarking using the System Usability Scale has established that digital health applications typically achieve mean SUS scores ranging from fifty to eighty depending on design quality and user familiarity with digital tools (Hyzy et al., 2022). Comparison of usability evaluation methods for health information systems has shown that SUS provides a quick, validated measurement that complements other usability assessment approaches (Farzandipour et al., 2022). Administration of the SUS to diverse user groups including clinical staff, patients, and administrative users provides insights into whether the system meets usability needs across stakeholder populations. For American Hospital Inc., SUS assessment will be administered to three user groups comprising staff dashboard users, individual patient portal users, and agency representative portal users, targeting a mean score of sixty-eight or above to indicate acceptable usability across all groups.

#### **2.8.2 ISO/IEC 25010:2023 Software Quality Characteristics**

ISO/IEC 25010:2023 defines software quality characteristics that enable systematic evaluation of healthcare information systems across multiple dimensions (ISO/IEC 25010:2023, n.d.). The standard identifies eight quality characteristics: functional suitability, performance efficiency, compatibility, usability, reliability, security, maintainability, and portability. Quality assessment models based on ISO/IEC 25010 have been applied to evaluate e-learning platforms and healthcare applications, providing structured approaches for comprehensive quality evaluation (Marroquin & Rodriguez, 2023).

Functional suitability measures whether all planned features work correctly and whether data retrieval from CIS modules is accurate. Performance efficiency is evaluated through page load time measurements targeting two-second thresholds and concurrent user load testing representing twenty to thirty staff users and fifty to one hundred external users. Compatibility is verified through integration testing with existing CIS modules to confirm absence of conflicts. Usability is assessed through System Usability Scale scores and task completion metrics. Reliability is monitored through uptime tracking targeting ninety-nine percent availability and error rate measurement. Security is examined through vulnerability scanning using open-source tools and manual penetration testing to identify common vulnerabilities. Maintainability is assessed through code quality review and documentation completeness. Portability is tested by verifying system operation on different server hardware within the local infrastructure.

#### **2.8.3 FURPS+ Requirements Framework for System Testing**

The FURPS plus framework organizes system requirements into five categories: Functional, Usability, Reliability, Performance, and Supportability, plus additional considerations (Marroquin & Rodriguez, 2023). Functional requirements specify what the system must do, including staff dashboard monitoring, patient progress tracking, agency result access, automated status aggregation from CIS modules, and email notification delivery. Usability requirements address user experience including interface clarity, navigation consistency, response feedback, and accessibility. Reliability requirements specify uptime targets, error recovery procedures, and data integrity preservation. Performance requirements define response time thresholds, concurrent user capacity, and throughput targets. Supportability requirements address documentation, code maintainability, system configuration, and administrative functions.

FURPS plus testing methodology ensures comprehensive coverage of both functional and non-functional requirements through systematic test case development and execution. Each requirement is mapped to specific test cases that verify both happy-path scenarios and error conditions. For American Hospital Inc., FURPS plus organization ensures that testing addresses all dimensions of system quality and that evaluation results provide evidence of readiness across functional, usability, reliability, performance, and supportability dimensions.

#### **2.8.4 Time-and-Motion Studies in Healthcare Operations**

Time-and-motion studies provide quantitative data about how long specific tasks consume and how workflow patterns change before and after system implementation. Studies on time-motion analysis methodology in healthcare show that direct observation and timestamp recording at key workflow transitions yield objective performance data (Al-Moteri et al., 2023; Kalne & Mehendale, 2022). Systematic review of time-motion study purposes in healthcare identifies applications including workflow analysis, resource allocation optimization, and implementation evaluation (Kalne & Mehendale, 2022).

Time-motion studies adapted for secondary clinic contexts such as occupational health PEME facilities can measure patient flow through direct observation by recording timestamps at each department transition point to calculate cumulative waiting time and total cycle time (Karthikeyan et al., 2024). Measurement focuses on critical time points including patient registration, laboratory visit, radiology visit, other specialty examinations, physician review, and result release. Pre-implementation baseline measurement establishes current performance, while post-implementation measurement captures improvements and identifies remaining bottlenecks. Time-motion study methodology has demonstrated effectiveness in identifying operational improvements in outpatient and tertiary care contexts (Karthikeyan et al., 2024; Gelisanga et al., 2024). For American Hospital Inc., time-and-motion analysis will measure patient flow cycles before and after PEME system implementation to quantify improvements in waiting times, completion rates, and staff coordination efficiency.

#### **2.8.5 Pre-Post Quasi-Experimental Design in Healthcare IT Evaluation**

Pre-post quasi-experimental design assesses operational outcomes before and after system implementation by measuring changes in key performance indicators including completion rates, turnaround times, error frequencies, and staff coordination burden. This design methodology allows comparison of performance across the same facility and population under different conditions without requiring a control group, making it practical for single-site healthcare implementations (Mansoor et al., 2024).

Quasi-experimental studies in healthcare IT have documented improvements in process outcomes, staff satisfaction, and patient outcomes following system implementation (Mansoor et al., 2024). Evaluation methodology emphasizes the importance of pre-implementation baseline measurement, post-implementation measurement at defined intervals, and statistical analysis to determine whether observed changes are clinically or operationally significant. For American Hospital Inc., pre-post measurement will compare PEME performance indicators before and after monitoring system implementation, measuring documented changes in result collation incidents, status inquiry calls, certificate error rates, patient waiting times, and completion rate achievements for rush and regular examination classes.

#### **2.8.6 Patient and Staff Satisfaction Measurement in Healthcare IT Implementation**

Patient and staff satisfaction measurement captures user perspectives on system effectiveness, ease of use, and impact on their work or experience. Research on patient satisfaction with healthcare services emphasizes that satisfaction is a key outcome metric reflecting whether systems meet user needs (Ferreira et al., 2023; Bhatt et al., 2024). Studies show that waiting time, communication clarity, and perceived attention to individual concerns are among the strongest predictors of overall satisfaction (Bhatt et al., 2024). For healthcare IT specifically, user satisfaction with information systems correlates with adoption rates, system utilization, and perceived organizational success (Walle et al., 2023; Nadav et al., 2024).

Measurement approaches for satisfaction include structured questionnaires, focus groups, and individual interviews capturing user perceptions about system functionality, usability, impact on efficiency, and overall satisfaction. Research on information system success models emphasizes that satisfaction reflects system quality, information quality, and perceived usefulness from the user perspective (Walle et al., 2023). For American Hospital Inc., satisfaction assessment will use validated questionnaires administered to staff dashboard users, patient portal users, and agency portal users, measuring perceptions of system usefulness, ease of use, impact on their work or patient experience, and overall satisfaction with the monitoring and result access system. Qualitative feedback through interviews will capture contextual insights about system strengths, areas for improvement, and unintended consequences that quantitative measures may not capture.

### **2.9 Synthesis and Summary of Related Literature**

This section synthesizes research across queue management, real-time dashboards, patient portals, role-based access control, regulatory compliance, system architecture, user interface design, and evaluation methods. Evidence establishes that real-time operational dashboards effectively support agile decision-making, RBAC can be securely implemented in Philippine healthcare contexts, priority queue algorithms improve patient flow, email notifications enhance patient engagement, and hybrid paper-digital systems preserve medico-legal compliance while enabling digital coordination. However, no existing general-purpose healthcare system comprehensively addresses the unique combination of needs required for occupational health PEME operations: real-time multi-department workflow visibility, rush vs. standard priority handling, multi-role portal access, automated completion notifications, and full alignment with Philippine DOH PEME requirements (AO 2013-0006) and Data Privacy Act compliance. The proposed PEME monitoring and result access system synthesizes these research-validated best practices into a specialized, context-appropriate solution tailored to American Hospital Inc.'s occupational health examination workflows and Philippine regulatory environment.

### **2.10 Conceptual Model of the Study**

![][image2]

The **Input** block establishes the baseline conditions, core requirements, and constraints that drive the development of the proposed system. It begins with the identified problems, highlighting the operational inefficiencies of the current setup, such as high patient waiting times, delayed PEME  completions, and manual collation errors. To address these, the study assesses the Current System and Data, which consists of existing Computer Information System (CIS) modules, extensive paper-based records, and department transaction logs. From this baseline, the system requirements (FURPS+) and stakeholder requirements are formulated, emphasizing the need to transition to active digital encoding, establish a cloud-native architecture, and provide unified, real-time progress visibility for staff, patients, and agencies. Furthermore, the inputs are guided by strict compliance standards, including ISO 9001:2015, Department of Health (DOH) Administrative Orders (2012-0012 and 2013-0006), and the Data Privacy Act of 2012 (RA 10173). Finally, systems analysis tools such as gap analysis, process mapping (DFD/BPMN), and baseline time-and-motion studies serve as the empirical foundation for designing the new system.

The **Process** block details the technical methodology, architectural design, and development phases required to transform the inputs into the desired outputs. The project utilizes an Iterative and Incremental Development Methodology spanning four distinct iterations, with each iteration completing planning, requirements analysis, design, implementation, testing, and pilot deployment. The phase initiates with system design and modeling, utilizing UML diagrams and UI/UX prototyping to structure the application. This is followed by infrastructure setup, which establishes a robust cloud-native environment using Supabase PostgreSQL and Next.js/React, supported by CI/CD deployment pipelines. A critical component of the process is the core system integration, which transitions the clinic from legacy paper routing to active digital encoding by utilizing WebSocket subscriptions and package mapping logic for real-time tracking. Portal Development involves building role-specific interfaces for staff, patients, and agencies, integrated with automated notifications and PDF certificate generation. Concurrently, strict security implementations—Row Level Security, RBAC, and encryption—and rigorous system evaluations—load testing, usability testing, and OWASP ZAP vulnerability scanning—are conducted to ensure system integrity and security throughout the development lifecycle.

The **Output** block represents the final deliverables and the measurable impacts of the newly developed system. The primary functional deliverable is a fully functional, cloud-hosted web application equipped with dedicated portals, real-time dashboards, automated notifications, and comprehensive technical documentation. The deployment of this system is expected to yield significant performance outcomes, specifically measurable reductions in patient cycle and turnaround times, the elimination of manual collation bottlenecks, and improved completion rates for both regular and rush PEMEs. In terms of reliability and usability, the system targets high System Usability Scale (SUS) scores, the efficient handling of concurrent users, a 99% system uptime, and a drastic reduction in manual error rates. Ultimately, the system serves as a compliance achievement, ensuring verified adherence and audit readiness for ISO 9001:2015, DOH health information standards, and data privacy regulations.

The **Evaluation and Performance Test** component is anchored in ISO/IEC 25010:2023 software quality characteristics and the FURPS+ model, employing validated methodologies from recent healthcare information technology research to ensure rigorous, evidence-based assessment of system effectiveness. Time-and-motion study methodology, following the approach established by Vignesh et al. (2024) in their tertiary outpatient department study, will measure patient flow efficiency, cycle times, waiting durations per department, and staff coordination activities through direct observation and timestamp recording at each patient transition point, enabling precise quantification of process improvements through comparison of pre-implementation baseline measurements against post-deployment performance. Pre/post quasi-experimental study design, validated by Mansoor et al. (2024) in their evaluation of healthcare educational interventions, will assess operational outcomes before and after system implementation by measuring changes in key performance indicators including PEME completion rates, rush case turnaround times, error frequencies, and staff-reported coordination burden, using statistical analysis to demonstrate measurable improvements and establish causal linkages between system deployment and performance gains. System usability will be quantitatively assessed using the standardized 10-item System Usability Scale questionnaire administered to staff users of the dashboard and external users of the patient portal, following the benchmarking framework established by Hyzy et al. (2022) in their meta-analysis of digital health applications, with target scores of 68 or above indicating above-average usability and scores in the 70 to 80 range representing good to excellent user acceptance. Compliance and security audit will conduct systematic verification of regulatory adherence through structured checklist evaluation against ISO 9001:2015 quality management requirements, Department of Health medical information system standards, and Data Privacy Act provisions governing patient data protection, consent management, access controls, and audit trail integrity, ensuring the system meets all mandatory legal and operational requirements for deployment in a Philippine healthcare setting. These evaluation results create a feedback loop, informing iterative refinements to the system design and implementation processes and ensuring continuous alignment with research objectives and stakeholder needs.

### **2.11 Analysis of Alternatives**

#### **2.11.1 Criteria Rationale**

Six criteria guide the evaluation of alternatives for the PEME monitoring and result access system. Each criterion has a weight reflecting its importance to project success.

Table 2.2 Criteria Rationale

| CRITERION | WEIGHT | RATIONALE |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| Compliance | 5 | Solutions must support or enforce all requirements stipulated under ISO 9001:2015, Department of Health minimum standards for medical information systems, and the Data Privacy Act of the Philippines. Loss of compliance can result in loss of operating licenses and patient safety incidents. |
| Security and Data Control | 5 | The security of patient data, internal auditability, and on-premise control is critical in medical information management. Systems must robustly prevent unauthorized access, loss, and leakage, while remaining subject to internal oversight. |
| Total Cost | 4 | This reflects both initial investment and operational expenditure over the expected system lifetime, including all hidden costs such as licensing, updates, training, and support. |
| Integration | 4 | New solutions must interact effectively with existing administrative and clinical systems, supporting business continuity and safeguarding historical data. |
| Scalability | 3 | The chosen system must remain effective and cost-efficient as patient loads increase, and reporting as well as legal requirements evolve over several years. |
| Support | 2 | Ongoing access to troubleshooting, updates, and maintenance is vital to minimize system downtime and maximize business resilience, but is of lesser weight compared to other critical criteria. |

Compliance and security receive equal weight (5) because AHI operates under strict regulatory oversight. Loss of either creates legal and operational risk. Total cost (4) and integration (4) also receive high weight; the clinic cannot afford overruns, and new systems must coexist with existing workflows without disruption. Scalability (3) matters less immediately but becomes critical as the clinic's patient volume grows. Support (2) has the lowest weight because a well-designed system with solid documentation reduces ongoing dependency on external vendors.

#### **2.11.2 Alternatives Considered**

1. **Status Quo**  
   The present system: paper monitoring forms, logbooks, in-person record management, Messenger/email for results, and established manual audit/compliance routines. This approach is fully compliant with ISO 9001, DOH, and DPA through documentary controls and strict staff procedure, and has repeatedly passed regulatory audits.  
2. **Bespoke Solution**  
   A bespoke, on-premise web solution developed for AHI, designed to fit exact PEME operational requirements, integrating real-time dashboards and secure portals for internal and external users. It is engineered to be fully aligned with existing partial-electronic, partial-paper processes and regulatory controls.  
3. **Commercial HIS \+ PEME Module**  
   A generalized, large-scale hospital information system provided by established vendors (e.g., Bizbox, Medsys). Includes various modules but is primarily targeted at general and specialty hospitals, requiring significant configuration or custom development to fit specialized PEME routines.  
4. **Cloud-based Patient Management SaaS**  
   A third-party subscription software platform (e.g., cloud EMRs, queue management SaaS). Allows fast online rollout and some workflow automation but hosts all sensitive data on external servers and offers only the configurability and compliance built into its shared-tenant model.  
5. **Enhanced Manual Process \+ Spreadsheet Tracking**  
   Current operations, but upgraded with staff-managed, shared spreadsheet solutions (Excel or Google Sheets) with macros for some real-time tracking and visual status, plus more rigorous manual data entry rules. This minimizes new cost while incrementally improving staff coordination, but still depends heavily on the discipline and skill of administrative staff.

   #### **2.11.3 Alternatives Decision Matrix**

   Five alternatives address the clinic's need to improve patient flow visibility and result access while maintaining compliance and security. The decision matrix evaluates each alternative against the six criteria using weighted scoring to identify the optimal solution.

##### **Status Quo (Score: 95):**

The existing AHI process is proven compliant and sustainable under current volume and legal scrutiny. Manual processes, secured via key-controlled records rooms, signed logs, and paper dispute trails, are reliable in the short term. Integration is complete by default, and costs are contained within administrative budgets. Scalability is challenging; as volume, scrutiny, or data mining demands increase, the ability to rapidly retrieve, search, or re-audit records declines, and error or loss risk rises. Support is fundamentally limited to staff retraining and procedural adjustment.

##### **Bespoke Solution (Score: 104):**

This alternative scores highest overall. It enables exact mapping to every regulatory procedure and reporting demand, ensuring robust compliance. By retaining all data internally, it offers multidisciplinary access controls, role-based security, granular audit logging, and rapid incident response – all critical under the Data Privacy Act. While development costs are higher than off-the-shelf solutions, the absence of ongoing license or rental fees balances these over the system's useful life. This approach minimizes integration risks, as the system is built using current AHI procedures as the blueprint, ensuring a smooth deployment and minimal staff disruption. The custom system’s scalability is directly tied to hardware and modular code, and can be expanded or enhanced incrementally. Although ongoing support responsibility lies with AHI or its designated IT partner, this burden can be managed with robust documentation and a phased skills transfer.

##### **Commercial HIS \+ PEME Module (Score: 85):**

This alternative supports compliance and generally employs international standards, though it is not guaranteed to fit every unique PEME scenario without expensive customization or consulting. Security is typically strong, but access and incident management may be fixed to software vendor paradigms and may be harder to audit fully. Total cost is comparatively high due to enterprise licensing, mandatory upgrades, and potential consulting fees. Integration is moderate at best, as large HIS often expects to replace legacy systems rather than meaningfully interoperate with them. Scalability is excellent, as these systems are designed for hospital networks, but this is often beyond the true requirements of AHI. Vendor support is excellent, though it can generate additional cost with service contracts and is not always responsive to highly tailored workflows.

##### **Cloud-based Patient Management SaaS Solution (Score: 77):**

Cloud-based solutions expedite deployment and offer built-in scaling advantages, but strongly underperform on compliance and local regulatory auditability. Storing sensitive patient information on global, third-party infrastructure complicates legal defensibility and creates latent risk for patient data governance. While monthly costs are accessible, expense rises with system usage and as modules/features are added. True, lossless integration with existing, sometimes paper-based, workflow is rarely possible. Although support is usually reliable and remote, it may not include expertise targeting the Philippines' unique regulatory constraints.

##### **Enhanced Manual Process \+ Spreadsheet Tracking (Score: 83):**

This alternative is immediately actionable, offers improvement in transactional traceability, and can be utilized with minimal or no new cost. Excel or Google Sheets offer process mapping and low-complexity dashboard functions. However, compliance and security depend entirely on staff discipline, experience, and adherence to evolving templates or checklists. As volume increases, coordination failures, inconsistent data entry, and recovery difficulties from data loss or corruption are real threats. Integration is seamless since all staff are already trained for manual administration, but support limitations and eventual performance bottlenecks make this a transitional, not permanent, solution.

#### **2.11.4 Matrix Discussion**

The results demonstrate that a custom-developed web application, hosted and controlled locally by AHI, provides optimal alignment with compliance demands, security, cost management, integration sensitivity, and the clinic’s future expansion direction. The existing manual process, while compliant and cost-efficient, fundamentally lacks the transparency, efficiency, and forward-compatibility now expected by client companies, agencies, and future regulators. Improved manual tracking is suitable as a temporary bridge but should not be considered a long-term solution. Commercial hospital information systems and cloud-hosted offerings provide some short-term wins but introduce either budgetary or regulatory exposures that outweigh their benefits for an ISO 9001-certified, compliance-focused outpatient clinic. The decision is thus substantiated by both operational evidence and best-practices decision analysis.

## **Chapter 3**

## **RESEARCH METHODOLOGY AND TECHNICAL BACKGROUND**

### **3.1 System Analysis**

This section translates the problems, objectives, and scope identified in the earlier chapters into a structured description of the proposed AHI PEME Information System. It defines the system boundary, the external entities that interact with the system, and the flow of information between them. The analysis focuses on how PEME cases, examination statuses, and result releases are recorded, monitored, and accessed by the different user roles. This provides the logical foundation for the detailed design, database structure, and functional and non-functional requirements presented in the succeeding sections.

#### **3.1.2  Context Data Flow Diagram**

The context diagram illustrates the Pre-Employment Medical Examination (PEME) system as a single, high-level process and identifies the numerous external entities that interact with it. The process encompasses all activities in conducting and releasing PEME results for clients and their employees.  
![][image3]  
Figure 3.1 PEME \- Context Diagram  
The patient entity is the individual applicant whose capability to work is being determined and who must provide all necessary entry information to begin the PEME process, including personal identification, personal information, medical history, the employment referral slip or medical request, and signed forms. The system is designed to acquire financial inputs through the patient, receiving either direct payment or charge account authorization, depending on the billing arrangement with the client company. In return, the system provides several key outputs for the patient: the official receipt, examination routing instructions, the monitoring sheet—with payment confirmation, if applicable—, and ultimately, a copy of their final PEME results or certificate.

The client company is the entity that formally requests the medical services for the applicant, thereby initiating the PEME process. In some cases, the company often handles the financial arrangement, providing the necessary charge account authorization when examination fees are billed rather than paid by the patient. After the PEME is completed, the system sends back the results in the form of a packaged set of documents containing the PEME certificate, billing summary, and a transmittal form.  
The reception entity forwards the validated documents, encoded personal information, and the initial PEME requirements of the patient to the system, and receives back the generated patient forms, monitoring sheet, and patient record confirmation. The billing clerk receives cash-slip or charge-slip data and provides verified billing endorsements. The system outputs the billing statements back to the billing clerk.

Multiple medical departments act as external entities, each receiving examination requests and patient exam details from the system and returning their corresponding examination results. These entities are responsible for conducting the requested medical examinations for the employees, including triage nurse, laboratory personnel, X-ray technologist and radiologist, ultrasound technologist and sonologist, PFT technician, audiometry technician, ECG technician and cardiologist, dentist, and medical examiner. Then, the nurse coordinator entity collates all the examination results into a collated patient chart. The medical director entity receives the patient chart and signs a draft PEME certificate. Finally, the nurse coordinator packages these results and confirms the transmittal preparation for delivery.

This includes receiving patient information, processing billing and payment, conducting medical examinations, and compiling and releasing PEME results.

Figure 3.2 PEME \- Level 0 Diagram  
The subprocess on receiving patient information, primarily managed by the reception staff, handles admission procedures. The process begins with the patient providing the necessary documents—identification, the referral slip or medical request, personal information, and medical history. Then, the clinic validates these documents, logs the patient details, prepares the necessary forms, and encodes patient information into the patient records data store. The output of this process includes the patient monitoring sheet, exam instructions, as well as a billing endorsement forwarded to the billing process.

Following the reception endorsement, the billing department performs the subprocess on billing and payment, receiving the patient encoded information and billing endorsement from the previous subprocess as inputs. Depending on the payment method, it generates either a cash slip or charge slip and records payment details in the Billing Records data store. The patient receives an official receipt and a paid monitoring sheet stamped as “PAID”. This paid monitoring sheet is then sent to the succeeding process as authorization to proceed.

Using the paid monitoring sheet and patient information from the Patient Records data store, the subprocess on conducting medical examinations is the core operational subprocess where all required diagnostic tests are performed—laboratory, radiology, ECG, ultrasound, dental, physical exam, and psychological evaluation test. All diagnostic findings are consolidated and stored in the exam results repository data store. These stored results become the primary input for the final compilation process.  
	  
In the final subprocess on compiling and releasing PEME results, all accumulated medical findings are consolidated, reviewed, certified, and officially delivered to the client company. Exam results from the exam results repository and patient information from the patient records data store are retrieved as inputs for this subprocess. The nurse coordinator collates and reviews all results from the various service units, prepares a transmittal form, and then transcribes the results into the final PEME Certificate Encoder Form. The medical director then signs the final certificate. This subprocess outputs the final PEME certificate, which is stored in the final PEME files data store. The packaged set of results are sealed and delivered to the client company along with a transmittal form.

#### **3.1.4 Explosion Levels** 

![][image6]  
Figure 3.3 Process 1 \- Patient Receiving Data Flow  
Process 1, patient receiving, manages patient check-ins and registration for pre-employment medical examinations. First, the patient provides all identification documents, referral slips, medical requests, and personal or medical history forms, as requisites to be validated by the reception staff. Once the documents are validated, the patient information and declared history are logged and encoded into the system, creating an official patient record stored in the Patient Records data store. After encoding, the system generates the necessary PEME documents such as the monitoring sheet, exam instructions, and patient forms. Concurrently, a photograph and signature are captured from the patient. When all forms and data have been completed, the patient is endorsed to the billing and payment process, along with the billing endorsement, monitoring sheet, and signed patient forms.

This process is the starting point of the operation’s reliance on a paper-based and department-segment system. The sub-processes, particularly 1.1 and 1.2, involve handling initial patient forms. Since the system lacks automated queue management or integrated flow monitoring at this entry point, the manual handling and documentation verification directly contribute to the fact that patient waiting time averages 2.6 hours across all departments. This reliance on physical records also contributes to the heavy manual burden later faced by the releasing staff and nurse coordinators involved when performing historical retrieval for re-medical examinations.  
![][image7]  
Figure 3.4 Process 2 \- Billing and Payment Data Flow  
Process 2, billing and payment, handles cash and charge payments and ensures that the correct amount is paid by the patients. The process begins when the documents—billing endorsement and monitoring sheet—from the previous process are received and checked by the billing clerk. This is to ensure that the correct examination package is assigned based on the patient’s company requirements or PEME referral details. Following this, the billing clerk prepares either a cash slip or charge slip, which serves as the basis for payment. The patient then proceeds to payment collection, where the cashier collects the cash payment, checks the correctness of the amount, issues an official receipt (OR), and marks the monitoring sheet as “PAID.” Details from the transaction—including the cash or charge slip, payment information, and receipt—are recorded into the Billing Records data store. The paid monitoring sheet is then forwarded to the medical examinations process, allowing the patient to proceed with their diagnostic tests.

From verifying billing endorsement to manually stamping on the patient monitoring sheet, like process 1, the time consumed in this sequential, manual verification and payment step contributes to the overall average patient waiting time to 2.6 hours. Furthermore, the lack of immediate status confirmation during this process means that external entities, particularly agencies, submit 50 to 60 status inquiries weekly because they cannot automatically verify if the patient has completed the initial administrative and payment phases.  
![][image8]  
Figure 3.5 Process 3 \- Medical Examinations Data Flow  
Process 3, medical examinations, encompasses all medical and diagnostic tests. It receives the paid monitoring sheet, signed patient forms, and patient information from the billing and patient receiving processes. The system first verifies the identity of the patient using these documents and prepares an authorized patient chart, which consolidates all encoded data and serves as the central reference for every diagnostic test. Using the authorized patient chart, the patient proceeds through a branch of examinations such as triage and vision checking, laboratory tests, radiology, ultrasound, ECG, pulmonary function testing, audiometric testing, dental examination, and physical examination. Each examination generates its own outputs, including vital signs and vision test results, laboratory results, x-ray images and interpretations, ultrasound reports, ECG readings, audiograms, dental findings, and physical examination findings. All these diagnostic outputs are submitted to the Exam Results Repository, where they are stored as part of the complete PEME result set of the patient.

The most significant operational failure occurs within this process, where the flow of patient requests and results is fragmented across numerous external medical departments. Figure 3.5 shows sub-process 3.1 connecting flows with entities like laboratory personnel and the X-ray technologist. Major bottlenecks can be identified in these points, where the examination is manually tracked through the patient monitoring sheet. This reliance on a segmented, paper-based system results in 224 documented result collation incidents monthly. In addition, because there is no systemic notification where departments finish their work, completed results remain idle for one to three hours after completion, as mentioned in chapter 1\.

![][image9]  
Figure 3.6 Process 4 \- Compilation and Releasing of Results Data Flow  
Process 4 involves the consolidation, certification, packaging, and final release of the patient PEME results. The patient examination results are retrieved from the exam results repository, along with their personal information from the patient records data store. These documents are collated and reviewed by a nurse-coordinator to create a collated patient chart. This chart is encoded and used to prepare the draft of the PEME certificate. This draft is then reviewed and formally signed by the medical director to create the official signed PEME certificate. Afterwards, the certificate and examination results are compiled into a PEME certificate package, which is forwarded to the client company. A transmittal form is also prepared and sent to the company to document the release of results. Concurrently, the signed certificate and collated patient chart are archived as a final PEME certificate file in their data store for record-keeping.

This final administrative process introduces failures related to quality control and finalization. The nurse coordinator manages sub-processes like 4.1 and 4.3, which require manually retrieving exam results from the exam results repository and patient information from the patient records. This necessary collation and transcription step is where data duplication occurs, such that all patient information is entered twice. This results in the documented encoding and transcription incidents that occur monthly, and leads to delays in release of results, where medical examinations fail to meet the time completion targets for both regular and rushed cases.

#### **3.1.5 Business Process Modeling and Notation (BPMN)**

![][image10]  
Figure 3.7 Process 1 – Receive and Admit Patient   
Figure 3.7 begins when the patient arrives at American Hospital Inc. and joins the queue at Reception. The patient waits until called to the counter. The receptionist then verifies identity through valid ID and checks the company referral slip and logbook entry. Patients with incomplete or invalid requirements are informed and advised to return once requirements are complete, while only those with complete documents move forward in the process.

For patients who pass verification, the receptionist opens the Admission module and searches for an existing patient record. If a record exists, demographic and employer details are reviewed and updated as needed, then saved. If no record exists, the receptionist encodes the patient’s demographic information, employer or agency details, and identifiers such as passport number, and the system creates a new patient record with a unique identifier. The receptionist then determines the type of PEME case based on the referral, such as initial PEME, re-medical, additional tests, or repeat exam, and whether it is land-based, sea-based, or country-specific. When necessary, the receptionist clarifies unclear instructions with the agency.

Once the PEME type is identified, an Admission transaction is created that links the patient record, the agency, and the case classification. The receptionist encodes an initial list of required examinations according to the employer package and age group, which Billing will later verify. The Admission transaction is saved, and the system generates a patient checklist or route form listing all departments the patient must visit, with spaces for signatures and time in and time out. The receptionist explains the next steps, hands the checklist and documents to the patient, and directs the patient to the Billing area. At this point, Process 1 ends and the case is handed off to Process 2\.

##### **Process Issue and Flow Mistake in Process 1**

In the current Process 1, Reception acts as a bottleneck because the queue and processing times are not measured or monitored. Patients wait in line without any recorded timestamps for arrival, calling, or completion, so staff cannot see how long patients have been waiting or how many are in the queue. Chapter 1 already identifies long waiting times and turnaround failures as key problems, but the admission process does not generate any data that would allow AHI to analyze or manage congestion at this entry point. This lack of basic time and queue monitoring in Reception is a process mistake because it hides a critical source of delay in the PEME workflow.  
![][image11]  
Figure 3.8 Process 2 – Assess Fees and Process Payment (Billing & Cashier)  
Figure 3.8 begins when an admitted patient from Process 1 is endorsed to Billing together with the monitoring sheet and supporting documents. The billing clerk retrieves the Admission transaction in the billing module, verifies that the patient identity, employer, PEME type, and initial list of examinations match the referral and company instructions, and checks that the monitoring sheet and signed forms are complete. If any information is inconsistent or incomplete, the clerk informs the patient and sends the case back to Admission for correction. Only when the endorsement is complete and correct does the billing clerk continue with costing.

For a correct endorsement, the billing clerk computes the total charges for the PEME package and any additional tests based on the verified exam list. The clerk confirms the payment mode, either cash payment by the patient or charge to the company. This decision is represented in the BPMN by a gateway that separates the flow into a cash branch and a charge branch. In the cash branch, the clerk prepares and issues a cash slip and certifies the bill. The cash slip, monitoring sheet, and documents are endorsed to the Cashier, while the patient proceeds to the cashier area and waits in the queue.

In the Cashier lane, the cashier calls the next patient in the queue, receives the cash slip and payment, and confirms that the amount is correct. The cashier issues the official receipt, stamps “PAID” and the receipt number on the monitoring sheet, and returns the receipt and paid monitoring sheet to the patient. The billing record in the system is updated to reflect full payment, and the transaction becomes ready for use by the examination departments. In the charge branch, the billing clerk prepares and certifies a charge slip instead of a cash slip. The charge slip and monitoring sheet are endorsed directly to photo capturing and the examinations flow, and the system records the transaction as a company charge rather than a cash payment. In both branches, Process 2 ends when the billing transaction is recorded and the paid or charge-endorsed monitoring sheet is forwarded to examinations.  
	

##### **Process Issue and Flow Mistake in Process 2**

In the current Process 2, Billing and Cashier perform separate manual verification, costing, payment collection, and stamping steps without any real-time link to examination progress or to the incident and turnaround metrics identified in Chapter 1\. Charges are computed and recorded per case, but the system does not automatically check that the final list of examinations billed is identical to the examinations actually performed, and it does not track queue times at Billing and Cashier or the number of cases waiting at each stage. Chapter 1 showed that result collation has 224 incidents per month and that overall waiting time averages 2.6 hours, with failures to meet 24-hour and 72-hour turnaround targets. However, the billing and payment process does not generate or surface the operational data needed to see mismatches between billed tests and completed tests or to manage congestion at the financial counters. This lack of integrated validation and queue monitoring in Process 2 is a flow mistake because it contributes to downstream collation errors and extended turnaround times, even though these are already recognized as major problems in the earlier chapters.  
![][image12]  
Figure 3.9 Process 3 – Conduct Medical Examination  
Figure 3.9 begins when the paid or charge-endorsed monitoring sheet and signed patient forms from Billing are received at the examination area. The patient proceeds to the examination waiting area, presents the monitoring sheet, and waits until called. The exam reception or nurse coordinator receives the chart, verifies the patient’s identity against a valid ID and the monitoring sheet, and checks that the PEME package, agency, and list of required examinations match what was endorsed from Billing and encoded in the system. If there are discrepancies or missing documents, the nurse coordinator clarifies the case or sends the patient back to Billing or Admission for correction. Only when the chart and monitoring sheet are complete does the nurse coordinator authorize the patient chart for examinations and log the start of the examination phase in the clinical information system.  
	  
Once the chart is authorized, the process enters the subprocess Conduct Required Examinations. In this subprocess, the patient moves between several clinical departments according to the required PEME package. At triage, the nurse records vital signs and vision findings on the chart and in the system. In the laboratory, staff collect specimens, run the ordered tests, and record results on laboratory forms and in the laboratory module. Radiology performs chest X-ray and issues a formal interpretation. Other departments such as ultrasound, ECG, pulmonary function testing, audiometry, dental, and physical examination follow similar patterns. Each unit verifies patient identity, performs the ordered procedure, documents findings on paper forms and logbooks, signs the monitoring sheet, and encodes results in its respective CIS module. The examinations may occur in different orders depending on patient flow and resource availability, and coordination relies on the monitoring sheet and department logbooks rather than a shared real-time status view. When the patient has completed the sequence of required examinations, the chart returns to the nurse coordinator, who manually checks the monitoring sheet and department outputs to determine whether all examinations defined in the PEME package have been completed and encoded before endorsing the chart to the next process for collation and final medical evaluation.

The system prints the spirometry result with key parameters (such as FEV₁ and FVC), which is then reviewed by the attending physician or pulmonologist. The physician documents an interpretation (normal, obstructive, restrictive, or mixed pattern) and this signed interpretation is filed into the PEME chart for final fitness evaluation.

Thresholds are plotted to produce an audiogram, which is interpreted to determine the degree and type of hearing loss, if any. The completed audiogram and interpretation are added to the PEME record to inform decisions for noise-exposed or safety-sensitive jobs.

The process then diverges based on the findings: if no disease requiring treatment is detected, the dentist issues a dental certificate indicating clearance for deployment; if active disease is found, the dentist issues a dental referral and instructs the patient to return with proof of completed treatment before clearance can be given. In both cases, the outcome (certificate or referral) is documented and linked back to the PEME record as part of the overall fitness assessment.

##### **Process Issue and Flow Mistake in Process 3**

In the current Process 3, examination progress is controlled by a paper-based and department-segmented system of monitoring sheets, charge slips, and manual logbooks rather than an integrated, real-time view of patient status across departments. Staff in each unit perform and encode their own results, but there is no automatic confirmation that all examinations required by a specific PEME package have corresponding entries in the clinical information system before the case is treated as complete. The nurse coordinator discovers missing or delayed examinations only during manual status verification across departments near the end of the process. Chapter 1 reported that result collation encounters 224 documented incidents monthly, including 85 pending laboratory results, 64 incomplete radiology submissions, and additional incomplete ECG, dental, physical, and psychology results, and that completed results can remain idle for one to three hours because releasing staff have no systematic notification when all departments have finished their work. Patient waiting time averages 2.6 hours and both regular and rush PEME cases fail to meet the 72-hour and 24-hour service level targets respectively.

This examination-stage design is a concrete manifestation of the structural problem identified in Chapter 1, which is the absence of real-time visibility into patient progress and examination status. Because Process 3 does not generate or expose continuous completion status across departments, staff must rely on manual status verification and paper-based coordination before collation and releasing can proceed. This process mistake directly contributes to the high number of result collation incidents, idle completed cases, and prolonged turnaround times that the study seeks to address.  
![][image21]  
Figure 3.18 Complete Chart & Release PEME  
Figure 3.18 starts when the nurse coordinator receives the authorized patient chart and examination results from the previous process. The nurse coordinator retrieves and collates records from the chart, monitoring sheet, and exam results repository, then checks whether all required results for the PEME package are complete and consistent. If any result is missing or inconsistent, the coordinator identifies which department is responsible and follows up with the concerned unit. In this case the process for that patient temporarily stops at the collating stage and only resumes once the missing results have been supplied. When all required results are present and consistent, the nurse coordinator proceeds to encode the final PEME certificate in the releasing module, selecting the correct template for land based, sea based or country specific formats and summarising the examination findings.

After encoding, the nurse coordinator reviews the draft PEME certificate against the collated chart and working forms. If there are encoding errors or omissions, the draft is corrected and updated in the system before being sent to the Medical Director. Once the draft is accurate and complete, the nurse coordinator transmits it to the Medical Director, who reviews both the PEME certificate and the supporting chart. If the Medical Director does not approve the certificate, it is returned for correction and the nurse coordinator revises the draft. If the certificate is approved, the Medical Director signs the final PEME certificate and the signed version is encoded and stored in the final certificates repository. The signed PEME certificate and supporting examination results are then sent to the releasing staff.

In the releasing lane, staff receive the signed PEME certificate and results, assemble the PEME package including the certificate, laboratory reports, imaging reports, and other required documents, and seal the package for release. The package is endorsed to the messenger who delivers it either to the patient or to the client company and obtains a signed acknowledgement of receipt. The messenger returns the signed acknowledgement to the releasing staff, who review it and confirm that the package was received by the correct party. Finally, the filing and records staff store the collated patient chart and final PEME certificate in accordance with the clinic’s filing policies and encode the completion of the case in the clinical information system, marking the end of the PEME episode for that patient.

##### **Process Issue and Flow Mistake in Process 4**

In the current Process 4, result collation and certificate preparation rely on a paper-based and department-segmented workflow instead of a single, reliable system view. The nurse coordinator manually retrieves results from multiple departments, checks completeness by inspection, and then re-types key findings and final decisions into the PEME certificate template. The Medical Director then reviews this manually compiled draft and, if errors or omissions are found, returns it for further manual correction and re-encoding. The same information is encoded again when the signed certificate is stored and when the completion of the case is marked in records. Chapter 1 reported that result collation encounters 224 documented incidents per month, including numerous pending or incomplete laboratory and radiology results and additional incomplete ECG, dental, physical, and psychology outputs, and that completed results may remain idle for one to three hours because releasing staff have no systematic notification that all departments have finished their work. These incidents include encoding errors, transcription errors, and collation errors that arise precisely because the final PEME certificate is constructed through repeated manual compilation and re-encoding of data that already exist in separate CIS modules. This design in Process 4 is therefore a direct manifestation of the structural problem identified in Chapter 1, the absence of real-time visibility and automated cross-checking of examination status and results and it contributes to the high collation incident counts and prolonged turnaround times that the study aims to address.

### **3.2 Program Design**

This section presents the technical design of the proposed American Hospital Inc. (AHI) Pre-Employment Medical Examination (PEME) Information System. The design specifies how the system will represent data, support user interactions, and enforce business rules in order to (1) provide real-time visibility of patient flow across PEME departments and (2) offer a secure web portal for authorized external stakeholders to access PEME result summaries.

AHI operates as a general clinic and diagnostic center that serves both PEME applicants and non-PEME patients. In this study, however, the proposed information system is scoped strictly to the PEME service line. As a result, the models that follow describe how the PEME module functions within the broader AHI environment rather than attempting to replace the hospital’s entire information system.

The models and specifications that follow are derived from the problems, objectives, and scope discussed in Chapter 1\. In particular, the design preserves AHI’s current sequence of PEME-related clinical steps and documentation requirements while introducing additional structures needed for queue monitoring, time-and-motion measurement, and controlled electronic access to results.

The system is designed using a UML-oriented approach. The data structures are first articulated through a logical data model and data dictionary; the functional scope is then expressed by the use case model; and the static and dynamic behaviour is captured by class diagrams, sequence diagrams, activity diagrams, and statecharts. These models serve as the blueprint for implementation and as the basis for defining and validating the functional and non-functional requirements that will be evaluated in the latter part of the study.

#### **3.2.1 External Design**

The proposed AHI PEME Information System utilizes a modern, decoupled cloud-native architecture designed for high availability, real-time synchronization, and cross-platform accessibility. The presentation layer is a Single Page Application (SPA) developed using React.js (via the Next.js framework) and styled with Tailwind CSS, utilizing a mobile-first, responsive design methodology. This ensures that internal complex dashboards scale efficiently on desktop monitors, while the external Patient and Agency portals automatically adapt to smartphone and tablet viewports, providing a native-like mobile experience without requiring users to download a dedicated mobile application.

The backend infrastructure is powered by Supabase, an open-source Backend-as-a-Service (BaaS) built on top of a robust PostgreSQL database. Supabase manages data persistence, secure user authentication, and WebSocket-driven real-time database subscriptions. External access for patients and client representatives is routed through secure HTTPS endpoints natively handled by the cloud hosting provider, ensuring the database remains completely isolated from direct public internet exposure.

To ensure strict compliance with the Data Privacy Act of 2012 (RA 10173\) and DOH guidelines, all health data is encrypted at rest (AES-256) and in transit (TLS 1.2+). Furthermore, while the primary deployment utilizes secure cloud hosting to facilitate seamless external portal access, the open-source nature of the Supabase stack allows the entire backend and database to be containerized via Docker. This provides a critical architectural fallback: should AHI's internal IT policies mandate strict on-premises data residency, the system can be deployed directly onto the clinic’s local servers without requiring codebase rewrites.

#### **3.2.2 Internal Design**

Internally, the AHI PEME Information System is organized around an API-driven, client-server model. The React frontend handles all state management, user interactions, and dynamic rendering of real-time queue dashboards and portal views. It communicates with the backend exclusively via secure REST and GraphQL APIs provided by the Supabase client library.

The backend layer enforces strict business logic and data security directly at the database level using PostgreSQL Row Level Security (RLS). Instead of relying solely on application-layer checks, RLS policies dictate that external users, such as patients or agency representatives, can only query rows where the associated identifier matches their cryptographic authentication token.

Because clinical staff will actively encode examination findings directly into the PEME system, the application operates as a specialized EMR module. When a department staff member submits a clinical result, the backend instantly broadcasts a payload via WebSockets to all subscribed clients. This triggers real-time updates on the Reception, Releasing, and Medical Director dashboards simultaneously, entirely eliminating the need for manual page refreshes and resolving the manual polling bottlenecks identified in Chapter 1\. Where necessary, the system can utilize secure API endpoints to cross-reference patient admission or billing data from the legacy Clinical Information System (CIS), establishing a unified, single source of truth for the releasing staff.

#### **3.2.3 Data Structures of the Program**

This section describes the data design of the AHI PEME Information System. Building on the three-tier architecture described in Section 3.1 and the selection of a bespoke PEME module in Chapter 2, it specifies how information about patients, companies, PEME cases, departmental visits, clinical results, and user activity is structured and stored. The data structures are scoped strictly to the Pre-Employment Medical Examination service line and are designed to support real-time queue monitoring, time-and-motion measurement, reduction of result collation and encoding errors, and controlled viewing of released PEME results.

##### **Overview of Data Architecture**

The system uses a centralized relational database as the authoritative repository for PEME information. The database resides in the data layer of the three-tier architecture and is accessed only through the application services described in Section 3.1.2. All internal users interact with the data through the staff dashboard and role-specific screens, while external users access released results through the patient and client representative portals.

The database stores only PEME-related information. Non-PEME encounters such as outpatient visits, emergency care, and general diagnostics continue to be recorded in AHI’s existing systems, which the PEME module may consult through read-only interfaces when necessary. This approach aligns with the system scope and the decision in Chapter 2 to implement a PEME-focused module rather than replace the broader hospital information system.

The schema contains three groups of data elements:

* Core operational entities that represent the PEME workflow, including patients, companies, PEME cases, departmental visits, structured results, and physician decisions.  
  * Security and audit entities that represent user accounts, roles, and audit logs.  
  * Configuration entities that represent departments, PEME packages, and status codes.


  Indexes are defined on key columns such as case identifiers, patient identifiers, department identifiers, status fields, and timestamps to support responsive queue views and reporting as the database grows. Archiving flags and status-based access rules are included to support long-term data retention and privacy compliance.


  This separation of operational, configuration, and security entities supports data integrity, maintainability, and security. It also contributes to the functional suitability, performance efficiency, reliability, and security characteristics discussed in the ISO and IEC quality section of this chapter.

  ##### **Core Operational Entities**

  The core operational entities reflect the PEME journey from registration through departmental visits, completion of tests, physician decision-making, and releasing. The same data structures used during operations also generate the indicators used in Chapter 1 and in the evaluation procedure, including waiting times, completion rates, error incidents, and result visibility.

  ##### **Patient**

  The Patient entity represents a person undergoing one or more PEME examinations. A patient may have multiple PEME cases over time, but each PEME case belongs to exactly one patient. For non-PEME encounters, the hospital’s existing systems remain the primary record; within this PEME module, the patient record serves as the parent for all PEME cases and their associated departmental visits and results.

  ##### **Company**

  The Company entity represents an agency, employer, or client organization that sends workers for PEME. A company may have multiple PEME cases linked to it, but each PEME case is associated with at most one company. This supports accurate reporting and controlled portal access for authorized client representatives.

  ##### **PEME Case**

  The PEME Case entity serves as the central record for a single PEME episode. Each case is linked to exactly one patient and to one company when applicable. A PEME case must include at least one department visit and may include several, depending on the required package and additional tests requested.


  A PEME case stores data such as the case identifier, patient identifier, company identifier, PEME package, case category, rush indicator, registration time, and overall case status. Case statuses follow the lifecycle defined in the state diagram, which includes Registered, In Progress, Pending Additional Tests, For Decision, For Releasing, Released, and Archived. These statuses and timestamps support measurement of case completion and cycle times relative to baseline metrics reported in Chapter 1\.

  ##### **Department Visit**

  The Department Visit entity represents a single visit of a PEME case to a named clinical department such as Laboratory, Radiology, ECG, Psychology, Dental, or Physical Examination. Each department visit is linked to exactly one PEME case. A PEME case must have at least one visit and may have several if multiple tests or follow-up examinations are required.


  The system records the department involved, the queue number, the current visit status such as Waiting, Called, In Service, On Hold, Completed, or Cancelled, and timestamps indicating when the visit was queued, when the patient was called, when the service began, and when the service was completed. These timestamps and statuses form the basis for real-time queue monitoring and time-and-motion measurement. They allow the system to compute waiting and service times per department and across the entire PEME workflow, and they are used to evaluate improvements over the baseline waiting time of two point six hours.


  ##### **Result Item**

  The Result Item entity captures structured findings produced by clinical departments. Examples include laboratory test values, radiology impressions, ECG interpretations, psychological assessments, and physical examination findings. Each result item belongs to one department visit. A department visit may have none, one, or many result items depending on the nature of the tests performed.


  Each result item includes information such as test code, description, measured value, reference range, units, abnormality indicators, and verification status. Structured results support accurate collation for physician review and reduce missing or duplicated entries, directly addressing errors identified in Chapter 1\.

  ##### **PEME Decision**

  The PEME Decision entity records the physician’s overall assessment once all required department visits are completed. A PEME case may have only one decision record. The decision includes the decision type, decision timestamp, and remarks or recommendations. The decision record determines whether a PEME case may move to releasing and whether results may become visible to external users through the portal.

  ##### **Security and Audit Entities**

  **User Account**

  The User Account entity represents an individual who can access the system. Each user account is linked to one role. The account stores login credentials or external authentication identifiers, user information, and account status.


  **Role**

  The Role entity defines a set of permissions associated with a user group such as reception staff, triage staff, department staff, physicians, releasing staff, client representatives, or system administrators. Each role may be assigned to multiple user accounts.


  **Audit Log**

  The Audit Log entity records sensitive actions that require traceability. These include logins, status changes, result updates, physician decisions, releasing actions, and portal views of medical results. Each audit log entry is linked to one user account and records what action occurred, which record was affected, and the exact time of the action. These entities implement role-based access control and auditability and support the security requirements and quality characteristics defined in the later sections of this chapter.


  ##### **Configuration and Reference Entities**

  **Department**

  The department entity stores the list of clinical departments that participate in PEME. Each department may be referenced by multiple department visits and schedule records. This table supports changes to departmental structure without modifying source code.


  **Package**

  The Package entity stores the standard PEME packages offered by AHI. Each package may be referenced by many PEME cases. The package determines the set of departments and tests that must be completed for a given case.


  **Status Code**

  The Status Code entity defines the allowable status values used by PEME cases and department visits. Each status code may be used by many cases or visits. Aligning these values with the lifecycle defined in the state diagrams ensures consistency across the data model and application logic.


  By keeping departments, packages, status codes, and schedules in editable master tables, administrators can make operational adjustments without modifying the application. These configuration entities complement the operational, security, and audit structures and complete the data model that will be implemented in the database and referenced in detail in the ERD and data dictionary in the following sections.

  #### **3.2.4 Use Case Diagram**

  The use case diagrams in this section describe how different actors interact with the AHI PEME Information System to accomplish their PEME-related responsibilities. Because the system is scoped specifically to the PEME service line, each use case focuses on registering and managing PEME cases, updating departmental processing and results, issuing fitness decisions, releasing cases, and providing controlled portal access to released summaries.


  At the system level, the AHI PEME Information System is represented as a single boundary that exposes use cases to external actors through a web-based interface. All interactive actors authenticate through a common login process before accessing role-specific functions, and each use case represents a distinct goal that contributes to the end-to-end PEME workflow. The overview first presents the main actors and use cases at a system level, after which the subsequent diagrams, Figures 3.5.1 to 3.5.8, detail the responsibilities and interactions of each actor group: Reception and Billing Staff, Triage Nurse, Department Staff, Physician, Releasing Staff, Client Representative, Patient, and System Administrator.

##### **Use Case Diagram Overview**

The overview use case diagram shows the eight primary actors that interact with the AHI PEME Information System and the shared and role-specific use cases available to them. All staff-facing actors and the client representative depend on a common Login use case that authenticates their credentials, checks account status, and establishes their role.

Once authenticated, internal staff see a role-based dashboard that allows them to search and view PEME cases or queues relevant to their responsibilities. The reception and billing staff initiate and update cases. The triage nurse performs initial clinical assessments and marks cases as ready for departments. Department staff manage queues and encode results for their respective departments. The physician reviews consolidated information and records the fitness decision. The Releasing Staff performs final verification, updates case status to Released, and controls portal visibility. The client representative uses a separate portal view to access released summaries for workers associated with their company. The patient uses a dedicated portal to view the status and released summary of their own PEME case. The system administrator maintains accounts, roles, configuration data, and audit logs. The system administrator maintains accounts, roles, configuration data, and audit logs but does not participate directly in clinical or releasing activities.
