#### **3.2.5 Class Diagram**

The class diagram specifies the static object-oriented structure of the AHI PEME Information System. It formalizes the main business concepts, their data attributes, and the relationships among them, and serves as the blueprint for the implementation of the application layer. The classes are derived from the entities identified in the data structures, the existing PEME workflow captured in the DFD and BPMN models, and the functional behaviour described in the use cases.

##### **Domain Model Classes**

![][image35]  
Figure 3.32 Domain Model Classes  
The class diagram in Figure 3.28 presents the core domain model of the AHI PEME Information System. It focuses on the main business objects and their relationships, independent of user interface and technical implementation details. The diagram serves as the conceptual bridge between the data structures in Section 3.2 and the behavioral models in the rest of this chapter.

At the center of the model is the PemeCase class, which represents one Pre-Employment Medical Examination episode for a specific patient and a company. The Patient class holds demographic and identifying information, while the Company class represents client organizations or manning agencies. Each Patient may be linked to zero or more PemeCase objects over time, and each PemeCase is associated with exactly one Patient and at most one sponsoring Company. PemeCase encapsulates case-level attributes such as caseNumber, packageType, caseCategory, isRush, registrationTimestamp, triageCompletedAt, overallStatus, releasedAt, and portalVisible. Its methods represent the main lifecycle transitions used in the PEME workflow.

Within a PEME case, departmental processing is modelled by the Department and DepartmentVisit classes. The department represents clinical service units involved in PEME and provides a master list of active departments. A single PemeCase has one or more DepartmentVisit instances, each linked to exactly one Department. DepartmentVisit captures per-department operational details: queueNumber, visitStatus such as Waiting, Called, In\_Service, On\_Hold, Completed, Cancelled, timeQueued, timeStarted, timeCompleted, and remarks, support queue management and time-and-motion analysis. DepartmentVisit objects in turn aggregate zero or more ResultItem objects, which store structured clinical findings. ResultItem includes attributes such as testName, value, unit, referenceRange, isAbnormal, verificationStatus, verifiedBy, and verifiedAt, and exposes behaviors like markVerified and isOutOfRange to support result verification and flagging of abnormal findings.

The PemeDecision class records the physician’s final evaluation of a PemeCase. Each PemeCase may have at most one PemeDecision, containing fitnessStatus, remarks, physicianUserId, and decisionDate. Methods such as isFitToWork and isPending reflect the key decision states that drive releasing and portal visibility. Once a decision is present and all required DepartmentVisit instances are completed, PemeCase can transition to For\_Releasing and eventually Released, at which point portalVisible and releasedAt are updated.

Security and accountability are handled by the User, Role, and AuditLog classes. User represents internal staff and, where applicable, portal accounts, with attributes such as username, passwordHash, isActive, and lastLoginAt, and operations for authenticate, changePassword, and deactivate. Each User is linked to exactly one Role, which defines high-level access categories and provides a hasPermission operation for permission checks at the application level. The AuditLog class captures sensitive actions performed by users identified by actionType, timestamp, details, and ipAddress and is associated with the User that created each entry. This domain model is intentionally scoped to PEME-related activities; non-PEME encounters at AHI are handled by existing systems and are not represented as classes in this diagram.

#### **3.2.6 Sequence Diagrams**

This subsection presents UML sequence diagrams for the main scenarios of the AHI PEME Information System. Each diagram shows how actors, user interface components, application services, domain objects, and the database interact over time to carry out a specific PEME-related use case. The diagrams are derived from the core PEME use cases identified in Section 3.3 and are consistent with the domain classes defined in Section 3.4 and the data structures in Section 3.2.

##### **Selection of Scenarios:**

Sequence diagrams were prepared for four scenarios that represent the core functional behavior of the system across the PEME lifecycle:

1. Registering a PEME case at reception.  
2. Managing departmental queues and updating visit status.  
3. Approving the physician’s PEME decision and finalizing the case for release.  
4. Viewing a released PEME result summary through the portal.

   These scenarios illustrate how the system supports PEME case registration, departmental processing, decision-making, administrative releasing, and controlled external access to released results.

   ##### **Sequence Diagram – Register PEME Case**

![][image36]  
Figure 3.33 Register PEME Case  
Figure 3.29 shows the sequence diagram for the Register PEME Case scenario. The reception and billing staff interacts with the DashboardUI to log in and open the registration form. The DashboardUI calls AuthService to authenticate the user, then passes the encoded case data to PemeCaseService. The service looks up or creates the corresponding Patient record, creates a new PemeCase, and invokes the Database to persist the case. The service then returns a confirmation with the assigned case identifier, which the DashboardUI displays to the staff.

##### **Sequence Diagram – Manage Department Visit and Update Queue**

![][image37]  
Figure 3.34 Manage Department Visit and Update Queue  
Figure 3.30 shows how department staff use the system to view and update their PEME departmental queue. After the staff member requests the queue, the Dashboard UI calls QueueService, which retrieves active DepartmentVisit records for the department from the database and returns the list for display. While the queue is on screen, the staff member selects visits and changes their status, such as from Waiting to Called, In Service, Completed, or Cancelled. Each change is sent from the Dashboard UI to QueueService, which applies the changeStatus operation on the corresponding DepartmentVisit, updates key timestamps like timeQueued, timeStarted, and timeCompleted, and saves the modified visit to the database before refreshing the queue display. This interaction aligns with the class diagram where PemeCase aggregates DepartmentVisit objects and with the functional requirements for real-time queue monitoring and service time measurement.

##### 

##### **Sequence Diagram – Approve Decision and Finalize PEME Case**

![][image38]  
Figure 3.35 Approve Decision and Finalize PEME Case  
Figure 3.31 shows how the Physician and Releasing Staff complete the final stages of a PEME case. First, the Physician uses the Medical Dashboard UI to open a case summary. The UI calls DecisionService, which loads the PEME case, departmental visits, and ResultItem data from the database and returns a consolidated summary for review. After reviewing the findings, the Physician submits a fitness decision and remarks. The Medical Dashboard UI sends this to DecisionService, which updates the PemeCase in memory, saves a PemeDecision record, and sets the case status to For Releasing in the database. In the second part of the diagram, Releasing Staff open the list of cases that are For Releasing through the Releasing Dashboard UI. The UI calls ReleaseService, which retrieves eligible cases from the database and displays them. When Releasing Staff choose to finalize a case, the UI calls ReleaseService to verify completeness, update the PEME case as Released with a release timestamp and portalVisible flag set to true, and insert an audit log entry. The Releasing Dashboard UI then confirms successful releasing to the staff member. This interaction matches the class diagram where PemeCase aggregates PemeDecision and carries releasedAt and portalVisible attributes, and it supports the functional requirements for physician decision, administrative releasing, and controlled portal visibility.

##### **Sequence Diagram – View PEME Result Summary**

![][image39]  
Figure 3.36 View PEME Result Summary  
Figure 3.32 shows how a client representative uses the portal to log in, search released PEME cases for their company, view a consolidated result summary, and optionally download that summary. The client representative first submits credentials to the Portal UI, which calls AuthService to validate the portal user against the database and returns a login result. After a successful login, the external user (patient or client representative) opens the search page and submits search criteria. For client representatives, the PortalService filters cases by company; for patients, it filters by the patient’s identity. The Portal UI invokes PortalService, which queries the database for PEME cases that are in Released status, marked as portalVisible, and associated with the representative’s company, then returns a list of matching case headers for display. When the representative selects a specific case, the Portal UI calls PortalService to load the released PEME case together with its PemeDecision and aggregated ResultItem data from the database and returns a caseSummary that the UI renders as a result view. If the representative chooses to download the summary, the Portal UI requests a downloadable version from PortalService, which logs the view or download action in the AuditLog table and returns a file for download. This interaction is consistent with the use cases for portal search and viewing, the class diagram where PemeCase aggregates PemeDecision and ResultItem and carries releasedAt and portalVisible attributes, and the functional requirements for secure, company scoped access to released PEME result summaries.

#### **3.2.7 Activity Diagrams**

This subsection presents UML activity diagrams that describe the main workflows supported by the AHI PEME Information System. Unlike the BPMN models used in the analysis phase, these diagrams focus on system-triggered activities and decision points that drive data creation, status changes, and access to PEME results. Two activity diagrams are included: one for internal patient flow monitoring across departments and one for external result access through the portal.

##### **Activity Diagram for Internal Patient Flow Monitoring**

![][image40]  
Figure 3.37 Internal Patient Flow Monitoring  
Figure 3.33 shows the activity diagram for the internal PEME workflow, from case registration until releasing. The flow begins with encoding patient and company information, creating the PEME case record, and initializing departmental visits and queue entries. It then proceeds through triage assessment, departmental queue display and status updates, and a decision node that checks if all required departments have completed their visits. Once all departmental visits are completed, the system loads consolidated results, records the physician’s fitness decision, and sets the case status to For Releasing. The releasing step verifies case completeness, evaluates whether the case is ready for release, and, if so, updates the case status to Released, which marks the end of the internal flow and enables portal visibility.

##### **Activity Diagram for External Result Access**

![][image41]  
Figure 3.38 External Result Access  
Figure 3.34 presents the activity diagram for external PEME result access via the web portal. After a login, the client representative or the patient enters portal credentials, and the system authenticates the user, with invalid logins causing a loop back to the credential entry. After successful authentication, the portal displays a search or filter form, accepts search criteria, and retrieves PEME cases for the client company that are in Released status. A decision node checks if any matching released cases exist; if none are found, a No records found message is shown and the user can refine the search. If matching cases exist, the system displays a list of released cases, allows the user to select a case, loads the associated summary, decision, and key results, and then displays the PEME result summary with an option to download or print it, concluding the activity flow.

#### **3.2.8 Statechart Diagrams**

This subsection presents UML state diagrams that describe how key entities in the proposed AHI PEME Information System change status over time. The models focus on the lifecycle of the PEME case and the departmental visit, and are consistent with the status values and transitions used in the data structures, sequence diagrams, and activity diagrams.

#### **State Diagram for PEME Case**

![][image42]  
Figure 3.39 PEME Statechart Diagram   
Figure 3.35 shows the behavioral state diagram for the PemeCase entity. A case is created in the Registered state after reception encodes patient and company data and saves the case record. When at least one department visit is queued or in progress, the case moves to In\_Progress, reflecting that clinical activities are ongoing.

If the physician requests further examinations, the case may temporarily move to Pending\_Additional\_Tests, then return to In\_Progress once additional visits are queued. When the system detects that all required DepartmentVisit entries are completed, the case transitions to For\_Decision, indicating that it is ready for medical review. After the physician records the fitness decision, the case moves to For\_Releasing. Once releasing staff verify completeness and finalize the case, the state changes to Released, at which point the result summary becomes eligible for portal access. Finally, cases may transition to Archived when a retention rule or administrative action closes the record, representing the end of the case lifecycle.

##### **State Diagram for Department Visit**

![][image43]  
Figure 3.40 Department Visit  
Figure 3.36 presents the state diagram for the DepartmentVisit entity, which models the status of a single departmental queue item. A visit is created in the Waiting state when the system initializes department visits for a new case or when additional tests are ordered. From Waiting, staff may move the visit to Called when a patient is summoned, or directly to Cancelled if the visit will not proceed.

When the patient is actually attended to, the visit transitions to In\_Service. During service, staff may temporarily place the visit On\_Hold and later return it to In\_Service to resume processing. After examinations and data entry are completed, the visit moves to Completed, signifying that the department’s contribution to the case is finished. Both Completed and Cancelled are terminal states. The combination of all visit states for a case is used by the system to determine when a PemeCase can progress to For\_Decision and ultimately to Released.

#### **3.2.9 Entity Relationship Diagram**

![][image44]  
Figure 3.41 Entity Relationship Diagram  
Figure 3.37 shows the database schema of the AHI PEME Information System, with PEME\_CASE at the center. PATIENT and COMPANY provide the identities of the examinee and the sponsoring client, while PACKAGE and DEPARTMENT define configurable PEME packages and clinical service units. For each PEME case, the system records one or more DEPARTMENT\_VISIT rows that track departmental processing and associated RESULT\_ITEM rows that store detailed clinical findings. PEME\_DECISION stores the physician’s final fitness decision for a case. USER\_ACCOUNT and ROLE support role-based access control for internal staff, patient portal users, and client representatives, STATUS\_CODE defines the valid lifecycle states for cases and visits, and AUDIT\_LOG provides traceability for sensitive actions performed by authenticated users.

##### **Discussion of Key Relationships**

One patient can have many PEME\_CASE records, and one company can sponsor many cases, which establishes one-to-many relationships from PATIENT and COMPANY to PEME\_CASE. Each PEME\_CASE has one or more DEPARTMENT\_VISIT records and at most one PEME\_DECISION, reflecting the lifecycle from registration through departmental work to final decision. Each DEPARTMENT\_VISIT has zero or more RESULT\_ITEM rows, allowing multiple tests or findings per visit while still tying each result to a specific department and case. STATUS\_CODE standardises status values for cases and visits, ROLE groups permissions for multiple USER\_ACCOUNT records, and PATIENT and COMPANY each may own multiple USER\_ACCOUNT rows for patient and client representative portal access. Each user can create many AUDIT\_LOG entries, ensuring that all critical operations in the PEME workflow are auditable.

#### **3.2.10 Data Dictionary**

The database is implemented using PostgreSQL, housed within the Supabase infrastructure. To enhance security against enumeration attacks—particularly for publicly accessible portal queries—primary keys for critical operational entities, such as PEME\_CASE and PATIENT, will utilize UUIDs (Universally Unique Identifiers) in the physical database, though they are conceptually represented as standard identifiers in this dictionary.

Furthermore, the USER\_ACCOUNT table integrates directly with Supabase Auth. Password hashing (using robust algorithms like Argon2 or bcrypt), token generation, and session management are securely delegated to the built-in authentication service, ensuring enterprise-grade credential protection.

### **3.3 Functional Requirements**

This section specifies the functional behavior of the proposed American Hospital Inc. (AHI) PEME Information System. Requirements are grouped by user role and written as user requirements (UR) followed by detailed, testable functional requirements (FR).

User requirements describe the goals of the user, while functional requirements specify in measurable terms what the system shall do to support those goals. Each requirement is written so that it can be verified through inspection, testing, or review.

#### **3.3.1 Reception and Billing Staff**

1. Reception and billing staff shall be able to register PEME cases with complete patient and case information so that cases are correctly linked to companies, packages, and rush categories.  
   1. The system shall allow reception and billing staff to search for an existing patient by full name, date of birth, passport number, or government ID before creating a new patient record.  
   2. The system shall allow reception and billing staff to create a new patient record with required fields: full name, date of birth, sex, primary contact number, and at least one identification number before saving.  
   3. The system shall require the selection of a company before a PEME case can be saved.  
   4. The system shall require the selection of a PEME package before a PEME case can be saved.  
   5. The system shall require the selection of a Case Category value before a PEME case can be saved.  
   6. The system shall require the IsRush flag to be set to either Regular or Rush before a PEME case can be saved.  
   7. The system shall automatically generate a unique Case ID or Case Number when a PEME case is saved.  
   8. The system shall automatically record the registration time stamp when a PEME case is saved.  
   9. The system shall prevent changes to patient demographic data for a PEME case once the overall case status is beyond Registered, except for authorized users with elevated privileges as configured by the System Administrator.  
   10. The system shall not allow deletion of a PEME case once it has been saved; instead, cases that will not proceed shall be marked using a "Cancelled" or equivalent status.  
2. Reception and billing staff shall be able to monitor and filter active PEME cases during admission to support queue management and corrections.  
   1. The system shall provide a dashboard that lists active PEME cases with columns for patient name, company, case category, rush flag, and overall case status.  
   2. The system shall allow filtering of cases by registration date range on the dashboard.  
   3. The system shall allow filtering of cases by company on the dashboard.  
   4. The system shall allow filtering of cases by a rush flag on the dashboard.  
   5. The system shall allow filtering of cases by overall case status on the dashboard.  
   6. The system shall allow opening of a PEME case from the dashboard when the overall case status is Registered or In Progress.  
   7. The system shall prevent changes to patient demographic data once the case status is beyond Registered, except by authorized roles, to preserve audit integrity

   #### **3.3.2 Nurse**

1. The nurse shall be able to perform triage and readiness assessment for PEME cases scheduled for the current day.  
   1. The system shall allow the nurse to view a triage list of PEME cases in Registered or In\_Progress status that are scheduled for triage on the current day.  
   2. The system shall allow the nurse to filter the triage list by rush flag.  
   3. The system shall allow the nurse to open the triage form for a selected PEME case from the triage list.  
   4. The system shall record a Triage Completion Time Stamp for the PEME case when the nurse submits the triage form.  
2. The nurse shall be able to manage the triage queue and prioritize rush PEME cases.  
   1. The system shall allow department staff to open a clinical data entry form for a department visit currently in the In\_Service status.  
   2. The system shall allow department staff to actively encode and save required test results, flags, and clinical parameters associated with the specific examination package.  
   3. The system shall immediately broadcast a real-time WebSocket event upon the completion and saving of a department visit, updating the global case progress without requiring a manual system refresh.

   **Department Staff**

1. Department staff shall be able to manage departmental queues for PEME visits assigned to their department.  
   1. The system shall allow department staff to view a departmental queue that displays only DepartmentVisit records for the staff member’s department.  
   2. The system shall display for each entry in the departmental queue the patient name, Case ID or Case Number, rush flag, queue number, and DepartmentVisit status.  
   3. The system shall sort the departmental queue first by rush flag and then by TimeQueued.  
   4. The system shall allow department staff to change a department visit status from Waiting to Called.  
   5. The system shall allow Department Staff to change a DepartmentVisit status from Called to In\_Service.  
   6. The system shall allow Department Staff to change a DepartmentVisit status from In\_Service to On\_Hold.  
   7. The system shall allow department staff to change a department visit status from On\_Hold to In\_Service.  
   8. The system shall allow Department Staff to change a DepartmentVisit status from In\_Service to Completed.  
   9. The system shall allow department staff to change a department visit status from Waiting to Cancelled.  
   10. The system shall record the TimeQueued when a DepartmentVisit first appears in the departmental queue.  
   11. The system shall record the TimeStarted when a DepartmentVisit status changes to In\_Service.  
   12. The system shall record the TimeCompleted when a DepartmentVisit status changes to Completed.  
2. Department staff shall be able to review summarized test completion and flags for DepartmentVisit records using data from the existing clinic information system (CIS).  
   1. The system shall allow department staff to open a read-only result summary view for a department visit in completed status for their department.  
   2. The system shall display, in the result summary view, a configured set of key test indicators retrieved from the CIS.  
   3. The system shall not allow editing clinical test values or verification statuses stored in the CIS from within the PEME Information System.  
   4. The system shall display a notification when no result data is yet available from the CIS for a DepartmentVisit marked Completed.

   #### **3.3.3 Physician**

1. The physician shall be able to review consolidated PEME case findings and record a fitness decision.  
   1. The system shall allow the physician to view a list of PEME cases in the For\_Decision status.  
   2. The system shall allow the physician to open a case summary that displays patient demographics, company, package, case category, rush flag, and overall case status.  
   3. The system shall display in the case summary a consolidated, auto-generated summary of all examination results encoded by the respective clinical departments, eliminating the need for manual chart collation.  
   4. The system shall display in the case summary a consolidated list of ResultItem entries grouped by department with values and normal flags.  
   5. The system shall allow the physician to select a fitness status value from a controlled list before saving the decision.  
   6. The system shall allow the physician to enter decision remarks as free text with a configured maximum length.  
   7. The system shall record the physician user identifier and decision time stamp when the fitness decision is saved.  
   8. The system shall allow the physician to review all encoded ResultItem entries, but restrict the physician from modifying raw data encoded by other departments to preserve audit integrity; only the final fitness decision and physician remarks may be edited.  
2. The physician shall be able to request additional examinations and revise decisions when needed.  
   1. The system shall allow the physician to change a PEME case status from For\_Decision to Pending\_Additional\_Tests.  
   2. The system shall require the physician to select one or more departments for additional tests before confirming the Pending\_Additional\_Tests status.  
   3. The system shall automatically create new DepartmentVisit records for each selected department when additional tests are requested.  
   4. The system shall update the overall case status from Pending\_Additional\_Tests to In\_Progress when additional DepartmentVisit records are created.  
   5. The system shall allow the physician to revise the fitness decision while the overall case status is For\_Decision.

   #### **3.3.4 Releasing Staff**

1. Releasing staff shall be able to verify PEME case completeness and finalize cases for release.  
   1. The system shall allow releasing staff to view a list of PEME cases in the For\_Releasing status.  
   2. The system shall allow releasing staff to open a release checklist for a selected PEME case.  
   3. The system shall display for the selected PEME case the completion status of each required DepartmentVisit.  
   4. The system shall display for the selected PEME case the presence or absence of a recorded fitness decision.  
   5. The system shall prevent finalization of a PEME case when at least one required DepartmentVisit is not in Completed or Cancelled status.  
   6. The system shall prevent finalization of a PEME case when a fitness decision record is not present.  
   7. The system shall allow releasing staff to confirm the final release of a PEME case that satisfies all checklist conditions.  
   8. The system shall update the overall case status from For\_Releasing to Released when final release is confirmed.  
   9. The system shall record the releasing user identifier and release time stamp when a PEME case is marked as released.  
2. Releasing Staff shall be able to generate release documents, control portal visibility, and trigger notifications for released PEME cases.  
   1. The system shall allow releasing staff to generate a printable PEME certificate for a released case.  
   2. The system shall allow releasing staff to generate a transmittal summary per company and date range that lists released cases.  
   3. The system shall mark a released case as portal-visible after finalization.  
   4. The system shall allow releasing staff to hide a released case from the external portal when internal correction is required.  
   5. The system shall require releasing staff to enter a reason when a released case is hidden from the external portal, and this action shall be recorded in the audit log.  
   6. The system shall record an audit log entry whenever portal visibility for a released case is changed.  
   7. The system shall automatically queue an email notification to the configured client representative email address of the case company when a released case is marked portal-visible.  
   8. The system shall record an audit log entry indicating whether the email notification for a released case was successfully queued or failed.

   #### **3.3.5 Client Representative**

1. The Client Representative shall be able to search released PEME cases for their company through the external portal.  
   1. The system shall allow the client representative to log in to the external portal using a username and password.  
   2. The system shall display only PEME cases that are in Released status, marked as portal-visible, and linked to the company associated with the logged-in client representative.  
   3. The system shall allow the client representative to search for released PEME cases by applicant name.  
   4. The system shall allow the client representative to search for released PEME cases by passport number.  
   5. The system shall allow the client representative to search for released PEME cases by registration date range.  
   6. The system shall display search results as a list with columns for applicant name, Case ID or Case Number, registration date, fitness status, and release date.  
2. The Client Representative shall be able to view and obtain PEME result summaries for released cases.  
   1. The system shall allow the client representative to open a PEME result summary for a selected released case from the search results.  
   2. The system shall display in the PEME result summary the applicant’s demographics, company, package, case category, rush flag, and release date.  
   3. The system shall display in the PEME result summary the final fitness status and decision remarks.  
   4. The system shall limit the PEME result summary for the Client Representative to a configurable subset of test findings and flags, as defined by the System Administrator in accordance with AHI policy.  
   5. The system shall allow the client representative to download a printable PEME result summary in a fixed layout format.  
   6. The system shall prevent the client representative from opening a PEME result summary for any case that is not in released status.  
   7. The system shall provide a mobile-responsive view of the PEME result summary, allowing client representatives to review fitness statuses clearly on mobile devices without horizontal scrolling.

   #### **3.3.6 Patient**

1. Patients shall be able to view the progress and final status of their own PEME cases and access released examination summaries without needing to ask staff at every step.  
   1. The system shall allow a patient to access a patient portal using a unique combination of identifiers (e.g., Case ID and date of birth or passport number), as configured by the System Administrator.  
   2. The system shall display, for an authenticated patient, the current overall PEME case status (e.g., Registered, In Progress, For Physician, For Release, Released).  
   3. The system shall display, for an authenticated patient, a list of required examination groups and their status.  
   4. Once a case has been marked Released, the system shall allow the patient to view a summary of findings and the final PEME decision, using read-only data from the existing clinic information system (CIS) and configured fields.  
   5. The system shall not display detailed clinical notes or raw test values beyond what the clinic’s privacy policy and Data Privacy Act provisions allow for patient portal viewing, as determined by the system administrator.  
   6. The system shall allow the system administrator to configure which summary fields and indicators are visible in the patient portal so that only information approved under AHI policy is shown.  
   7. The system shall render the patient portal using touch-friendly UI components and responsive layouts, ensuring that patients can navigate the progress tracker and download PDF certificates directly from standard mobile web browsers.

   #### **3.3.7 System Administrator**

1. The system administrator shall be able to manage user accounts and roles for internal and external users.  
   1. The system shall allow the system administrator to create a user account with a unique username and an assigned primary role.  
   2. The system shall allow the system administrator to lock a user account to prevent login.  
   3. The system shall allow the system administrator to disable a user account permanently.  
   4. The system shall display the last login time stamp for each user account.  
   5. The system shall allow the system administrator to reset a user password through a controlled procedure.  
2. The system administrator shall be able to configure reference data for departments, packages, and status codes.  
   1. The system shall allow the system administrator to create a department record with a department name and active flag.  
   2. The system shall allow the system administrator to deactivate a department while preserving existing references.  
   3. The system shall allow the system administrator to create a PEME package record with a package name and description.  
   4. The system shall allow the system administrator to map a PEME package to one or more departments through a configuration screen.  
   5. The system shall allow the system administrator to activate or deactivate a PEME package.  
   6. The system shall allow the system administrator to define PEME case status codes through a configuration screen.  
   7. The system shall allow the system administrator to define department visit status codes through a configuration screen.  
   8. The system shall prevent deletion of a status code that is referenced by at least one record.  
   9. The system shall allow the System Administrator to create and maintain Company records with at least a company name and active flag.  
   10. The system shall allow the System Administrator to associate a Client Representative user account with one or more Company records to control which PEME cases are visible in the external portal.  
3. The system administrator shall be able to maintain audit logs, system parameters, and email settings.  
   1. The system shall record an audit log entry for each successful login.  
   2. The system shall record an audit log entry for each failed login attempt.  
   3. The system shall record an audit log entry for each creation, update, or deletion of a PEME\_CASE record.  
   4. The system shall record an audit log entry for each change in DepartmentVisit status.  
   5. The system shall record an audit log entry for each change in PEME fitness decision.  
   6. The system shall record an audit log entry for each change in case release status.  
   7. The system shall allow the system administrator to view audit log entries filtered by date range.  
   8. The system shall allow the system administrator to filter audit log entries by user account.  
   9. The system shall allow the system administrator to export filtered audit log entries to a secure file format for external review.  
   10. The system shall provide an administrative screen that displays the application version, database version, and last backup time stamp to support troubleshooting.  
   11. The system shall allow the system administrator to configure SMTP server settings used for outbound email notifications.  
   12. The system shall allow the system administrator to configure email templates for result-availability notifications sent to client representatives.

### **3.4 Non-Functional Requirements**

This section specifies non-functional requirements that describe how well the AHI PEME Information System must perform in terms of usability, reliability, performance, supportability, and security. All requirements are stated so that they can be quantitatively verified.

#### **3.4.1 Usability**

1. The system shall enable a trained reception and Billing Staff member to complete registration of an  
    existing patient’s PEME case in 5 minutes or less during pilot testing.  
2. The system shall enable a trained Department Staff member to move a DepartmentVisit from Waiting to In\_Service in 5 clicks or less from the departmental queue screen.  
3. The system shall enable a trained releasing staff member to locate and open a case in For\_Releasing status in 3 clicks or less from the releasing list.  
4. The system shall enable a client representative to log in, search for a released case, and open the PEME result summary within 2 minutes without using a printed manual during usability testing.  
5. The system shall display consistent navigation menus and page titles across all external portal pages as verified during interface review.  
6. The system shall achieve a System Usability Scale (SUS) score of at least 70 from 80 percent of participating internal users during post-deployment evaluation.  
7. The system shall achieve a System Usability Scale (SUS) score of at least 70 from 80 percent of participating external users, specifically client representatives, during post-deployment evaluation.  
8. The external Patient and Client Representative portals shall adaptively scale to fit standard mobile viewports, ranging from 360px to 428px in width, without requiring the user to horizontally scroll or manually zoom to read text.  
9. All primary interactive elements (buttons, links, dropdowns) on the mobile view shall maintain a minimum touch target size of 44x44 pixels to ensure touch accessibility.

#### **3.4.2 Reliability**

1. The system shall achieve at least 99.0 percent uptime during AHI clinic operating hours, excluding scheduled maintenance, as measured by server monitoring logs.  
2. The system shall achieve a mean time to repair of 2 hours or less for incidents that cause complete unavailability during clinic operating hours, measured from incident logging to restoration of service.  
3. The system shall guarantee that once a PEME case, DepartmentVisit, or ResultItem save operation is confirmed, the corresponding record exists in the database as verified by transaction logs.  
4. The system shall restore all committed PEME data after an application server restart without  
    requiring re-entry of previously saved records.

#### **3.4.3 Performance**

1. The system shall load the active PEME case dashboard for internal users in 3 seconds or less for at  least 95 percent of requests under a load of up to 20 concurrent internal users  
2. The system shall refresh the departmental queue screen in 2 seconds or less for at least 95 percent of requests under a load of up to 20 concurrent internal users.  
3. The system shall load search results for released cases in the client portal in 3 seconds or less for at least 95 percent of requests under a load of up to 10 concurrent external users.  
4. The system shall generate a printable PEME result summary in 5 seconds or less for at least 95 percent of requests during performance testing.  
5. The system shall support at least 30 simultaneous logged-in users, combining internal and external  
    users, without violating the specified response-time limits during performance testing.  
6. The system shall make a PEME case available in the external portal within 2 hours or less after the case status is set to Released, as verified by audit logs comparing the Release Time Stamp and the portal-visibility Time Stamp.  
7. The external Patient Portal shall achieve a First Contentful Paint (FCP) of 2 seconds or less and fully load within 4 seconds when accessed over a simulated standard 4G mobile network.

#### **3.4.4 Supportability**

1. The system shall utilize Continuous Integration/Continuous Deployment (CI/CD) pipelines via GitHub Actions or Vercel to allow developers to push code updates to the production environment seamlessly.  
2. The system's backend infrastructure shall be capable of being containerized via Docker to support transition to an on-premises local server environment within 4 hours, should clinic policy require it.  
3. The system shall allow changes to departments, PEME packages, and status codes through configuration screens without modifying application source code.  
4. The system shall store configuration values for departments, PEME packages, and status codes in database tables or configuration files that can be updated without recompilation.

#### **3.4.5 Security**

1. The system shall enforce a minimum password length of 8 characters for all user accounts.  
2. The system shall delegate user authentication, password hashing, and session token generation to a Supabase Auth, ensuring no plain-text or weakly-hashed passwords are stored in the application database.  
3. The system shall automatically log out inactive user sessions after a configurable inactivity period.  
4. The system shall restrict access to PEME case data based on assigned roles so that internal users can view only cases needed for their responsibilities as verified in role-based access control tests.  
5. The system shall restrict external portal access so that a client representative can view only released cases linked to the company associated with the representative’s user account.  
6. The system shall record an audit log entry for every successful login attempt with user identifier, time stamp, and source IP address.  
7. The system shall record an audit log entry for every failed login attempt with the attempted  
    username, time stamp, and source IP address.   
8. The system shall record an audit log entry for every creation, update, or deletion of PEME cases, DepartmentVisit records, ResultItem entries, fitness decisions, and release actions.  
9. The system shall allow authorized administrators to filter audit log entries by date range and user account.  
10. The system shall allow authorized administrators to export filtered audit log entries to a secure file format for external review.  
11. The system shall require HTTPS for all browser connections to the production web server using a valid server certificate.  
12. The system shall send email notifications for released cases using SMTP over TLS or a comparable secure email transport.  
13. The system shall ensure that email notifications for released cases do not include detailed medical  
     findings in the email body and instead direct recipients to log into the portal to view results.  
14. The system shall ensure that fields and indicators displayed in patient and client representative portals are limited to those explicitly configured as visible by the system administrator, in accordance with AHI’s privacy policy and Data Privacy Act requirements.

### **3.5 Project Details**

#### **3.5.1 Project Development Methodology**

The system development follows an Iterative and Incremental Development methodology organized into four iterations. Each iteration delivers functional system components, enables stakeholder review, incorporates feedback during development, and identifies technical problems before they become costly to resolve. Each iteration completes planning, requirements analysis, design, implementation, testing, and pilot deployment.

**Iteration 1: Cloud Infrastructure and Foundational Architecture**  
This iteration establishes the core cloud-native environment. The development team sets up the Supabase PostgreSQL database, configures built-in authentication, and initializes the Next.js/React frontend repository. Database schemas are migrated to establish normalized structures for patients, departments, and packages. Row Level Security (RLS) policies are implemented to secure baseline data access. Testing verifies secure frontend-to-backend API communication, user authentication flows, and the successful deployment of the web application via CI/CD pipelines.

**Iteration 2: Active Encoding and Real-Time Dashboard Expansion**  
This iteration develops the core clinical workflow, transitioning the clinic from paper routing to active digital encoding. Interfaces are built for Reception to register cases and for Department Staff to encode clinical findings directly into the system. Real-time WebSocket subscriptions are implemented so that as departments complete tests, the progress status automatically updates across all staff dashboards. Testing verifies that the package mapping logic accurately calculates completion percentages and validates that real-time state changes occur efficiently under concurrent user load, directly addressing the manual collation bottlenecks identified in Chapter 1\.

**Iteration 3: Patient and Agency Portal Development**  
This iteration creates two external-facing interfaces. The patient interface displays personal examination progress based on assigned package, showing completed tests, pending tests, and next required department. The agency portal enables recruitment agency representatives to view examination status and access results for their assigned workers. Secure authentication distinguishes staff users, individual patient users, and agency representative users with role-based permissions. The system generates downloadable PDF certificates. Email notification functionality triggers alerts to releasing staff, agency representatives, and patients when results become available in the portal. Security testing identifies and remediates vulnerabilities through OWASP ZAP scanning and manual penetration testing. This iteration addresses the 50 to 65 weekly agency status inquiries and provides patients direct visibility into personal progress.

**Iteration 4: Completion, Validation, and Deployment Preparation**  
This iteration fixes remaining defects, optimizes performance for 20 to 30 concurrent staff users and 50 to 100 external users, completes comprehensive documentation, and conducts full compliance review against ISO 9001:2015, DOH Administrative Orders 2012-0012 and 2013-0006, and Data Privacy Act requirements. The team prepares a production deployment plan, develops training materials, and conducts staff training sessions. The formal evaluation period for baseline and post-implementation data collection begins.

Between iterations, the development team incorporates feedback from clinic staff and stakeholders. Research activities are scheduled during low-volume operational periods and kept brief to minimize service disruption while maintaining continuous clinic operations.

#### **3.5.2 Evaluation Procedure**

The evaluation employs before-and-after comparison design collecting identical measurements pre-implementation and post-implementation (Mansoor et al., 2024). This approach measures system impact on documented operational problems.

#### **3.5.3 Pre-Implementation Baseline Measurement**

Direct observation records complete patient journeys from admission through result release following time-and-motion study methodology adapted from Karthikeyan et al. (2024). While their approach was developed for tertiary outpatient department workflow analysis, the fundamental observation techniques and timestamp recording methods apply to specialized secondary clinic workflows. Observers document 40 to 60 complete patient journeys capturing cumulative waiting time across all ten departments, total cycle time from admission to result availability, department-specific wait times, and manual coordination activities between units.

Baseline performance metrics include 2.6-hour average cumulative patient waiting time, laboratory 65-minute peak wait times, radiology 55-minute peak wait times, 224 monthly result collation incidents requiring 50 to 85 minutes daily staff time for manual status checking, 160 monthly encoding incidents from repeated data entry, 92 percent regular PEME completion rate representing 72 monthly failures to meet 72-hour targets, 89 to 90 percent rush PEME completion rate representing 11 monthly failures to meet 24-hour targets, and 50 to 65 weekly agency status inquiries.

Staff interviews document causes of delays including coordination challenges between departments, difficulties locating patient status without systematic notification of completion, bottlenecks in result compilation when releasing staff manually poll departments, and time consumed responding to agency status inquiries.

#### **3.5.4 Post-Implementation Measurement**

Following staff familiarization with the system, identical measurement methods repeat. Observers record patient waiting time to assess reduction from 2.6-hour baseline. Result release timing measures interval from final department completion to portal availability, targeting reduction in idle time of 1 to 3 hours when completed results await manual discovery by releasing staff.

System logs automatically capture complete patient journey timestamps enabling precise calculation without relying solely on manual observation. Portal usage metrics document access patterns by patients and agency representatives. Agency status inquiry frequency measures reduction from baseline of 50 to 65 weekly calls. Staff coordination time measures reduction from baseline of 50 to 85 minutes daily spent manually checking department completion status. Email notification delivery times are recorded to verify alert functionality.

#### **3.5.5 User Feedback Collection**

Staff users complete System Usability Scale (SUS) after a minimum of two weeks of use, focusing on whether the system helps locate patient status quickly and coordinate result releases without manual department polling (Hyzy et al., 2022). Patient portal users complete usability surveys assessing ease of viewing personal examination progress and accessing results. Agency portal users complete surveys evaluating status visibility and result access compared to phone or email inquiries.

Structured compliance audit checklist verifies Data Privacy Act adherence under Republic Act No. 10173, ISO 9001:2015 requirements, and DOH standards under Administrative Orders 2012-0012 and 2013-0006 through systematic review of documentation control, record management, security measures, and audit trail capabilities.

#### **3.5.6 Analysis and Comparison**

Statistical tests determine whether observed improvements exceed random variation. Analysis examines whether the system reduces 2.6-hour average cumulative patient waiting time, decreases 224 monthly result collation incidents, decreases 160 monthly encoding incidents, reduces staff coordination time from 50 to 85 minutes daily, decreases 8 percent regular PEME late completion rate, decreases rush PEME late completion rate from 10 to 11 percent, reduces agency status inquiries from 50 to 65 weekly, reduces idle time of 1 to 3 hours between department completion and result availability, and successfully delivers email notifications for result availability.

#### **3.5.7 Software Quality Characteristics**

System quality is assessed across eight dimensions using ISO/IEC 25010:2023 standard for software products in context of clinic requirements supporting 45 staff members, 50 daily patients, 1,000 monthly PEME cases, and maintaining 50,000 to 70,000 active patient records (International Organization for Standardization, 2023).

**Functional Suitability –** All planned features work correctly. Read-only integration accurately retrieves data from existing CIS modules without modification. Package mapping logic correctly matches completed tests against requirements. Staff dashboard displays accurate real-time status aggregated from CIS modules. The patient interface shows correct personal progress. Agency portal displays authorized worker information only. Role-based access control enforces permissions preventing unauthorized data access. PDF certificate generation produces accurate documents. Email notification system triggers alerts when results become available in the portal.

**Performance Efficiency –** Dashboard pages load within 2 seconds. Database queries return results quickly when searching through 50,000 to 70,000 patient records. Real-time status aggregation from multiple CIS modules completes promptly. Email notifications deliver within acceptable timeframes. The system handles concurrent usage by 20 to 30 staff users and 50 to 100 external users without degradation. Performance testing simulates peak conditions verifying maintained responsiveness under maximum load conditions reaching 60 to 70 patients during mid-week rush periods.

**Compatibility –** The system integrates with existing CIS modules through read-only database connections. It functions on clinic server infrastructure and network. The system does not conflict with existing operations where staff continue entering data into CIS modules following current practices. Email notification integrates with existing email infrastructure currently used for result distribution to agencies.

**Usability –** Users accomplish tasks quickly with minimal errors. Interface terminology matches how staff think about patient flow across ten departments. The internal staff dashboard utilizes expansive desktop layouts for dense data tables, while the external Patient and Agency portals employ a mobile-first responsive design. This ensures progress tracking and result access are straightforward and legible on smartphones. System Usability Scale scores target 68 or above, indicating above-average usability following Hyzy et al. (2022) benchmarking for digital health applications.

**Reliability –** The system operates continuously without crashing or losing data. Automatic recovery mechanisms restore operation after errors. Uptime target is 99 percent during clinic hours representing less than 24 minutes monthly downtime. Email notification system demonstrates reliable delivery of alerts.

**Security –** Patient data is protected from unauthorized access meeting Data Privacy Act requirements for managing 50,000 to 70,000 patient records and approximately 12,000 annual PEME examinations. Secure user authentication, encrypted data transmission using HTTPS, encrypted data storage, comprehensive audit logging of all access events, and role-based permissions preventing unauthorized viewing protect sensitive information. Read-only CIS integration eliminates risk of accidental data modification. Email notifications contain secure portal links rather than sensitive patient data.

**Maintainability –** Code is organized logically with clear documentation enabling future updates. Modular design allows component modification without affecting the entire system. Read-only integration approach simplifies maintenance by avoiding complex bidirectional synchronization. Email notification functionality uses standard protocols enabling straightforward troubleshooting and updates.

**Portability –** The system operates on different server hardware using standard database structures and web technologies. It avoids vendor lock-in through use of open-source technologies. Email notification uses standard SMTP protocols ensuring compatibility with various email service providers.

#### **3.5.8 Data Gathering Procedure**

**Document Review –** Clinic operating manuals, workflow procedures, audit reports, and historical records documenting 1,000 monthly PEME cases are examined. Particular attention goes to records showing 224 monthly result collation incidents, 160 monthly encoding incidents, 72 monthly regular PEME late completions, and 11 monthly rush PEME late completions.

**Direct Observation –** Trained observers watch complete patient journeys recording cumulative waiting time across departments and total cycle time following time-and-motion methodology adapted from Karthikeyan et al. (2024). Observation sessions span different days and operational conditions capturing both low-volume days with 30 to 35 patients and peak days reaching 60 to 70 patients. Observers document coordination activities, manual status checking procedures, and result compilation processes to understand sources of 2.6-hour average waiting time and delays causing missed deadlines.

**Surveys –** Staff and external users complete System Usability Scale containing ten standardized questions after a minimum two weeks of use (Hyzy et al., 2022). Custom surveys ask about improvements in patient flow visibility, result release timeliness, coordination effort reduction, and satisfaction compared to manual processes. Open-ended questions invite detailed comments.

**System Logs –** The system automatically records user activities including login times, patient status checks, result validation timestamps, portal access by external users, email notification delivery times and success rates, and all data access events. These objective records enable precise calculation of time from final department completion to result availability, directly measuring improvements in the releasing process.

**Interviews –** Individual conversations with 8 to 12 key individuals including department heads, frontline staff, administrative coordinators, and agency representatives explore how the system affects patient flow monitoring, result release coordination, email notification utility, and agency communication. Interviews are brief at 20 to 30 minutes and scheduled during convenient times.

All data collection follows ethical standards requiring informed consent, voluntary participation without penalty, confidentiality through anonymization, and scheduling minimizing patient care disruption.

#### **3.5.9 Population and Sampling**

The study population comprises three groups at American Hospital Inc. Staff users include all 45 employees across ten departments involved in pre-employment medical examination processing. External portal users include patients undergoing examinations and recruitment agency representatives managing worker deployments, drawn from a monthly volume of approximately 1,000 examinations. Patient journeys represent complete examination workflows from admission through result release.

**Staff Users**  
Survey participation targets 20 to 30 respondents from the 45-person workforce, representing 44 to 67 percent of total staff. Sampling includes diverse departments, roles, and experience levels. Time-and-motion observations document staff interactions across all ten departments.

This target is justified by statistical adequacy and operational constraints. Hyzy et al. (2022) meta-analysis of 37 digital health applications found that 20 to 30 participants provide reliable System Usability Scale mean score estimation with confidence intervals adequate to distinguish usability categories. The clinic cannot allocate all 45 staff simultaneously due to patient care requirements. The target balances statistical reliability with operational feasibility.

**External Portal Users**  
Targets include 20 to 30 external users from approximately 1,000 monthly examinations, split between patient users and agency representative users with minimum 10 to 15 respondents per subgroup. Participation is voluntary among portal adopters.

Early adopters may differ from non-users in technical proficiency, representing an acknowledged limitation. However, early adopter feedback identifies usability barriers and acceptance factors informing broader deployment. The target enables detection of group-specific patterns while remaining achievable given voluntary participation and the two to four week familiarization period required before valid feedback.

**Patient Journey Observations**  
Observations capture 40 to 60 complete patient journeys pre-implementation and post-implementation, representing two to three weeks of operations at 50 patients daily. Observations span different PEME types for land-based and sea-based workers, different company packages, different days capturing 30 to 35 patient low-volume days and 60 to 70 patient peak days, and different times including morning admission rushes and afternoon result releases.

Statistical power analysis justifies this sample size. Cohen (1988) guidelines indicate that detecting medium effect sizes defined as Cohen's d of approximately 0.5 requires minimum 34 paired observations for 80 percent power at significance level 0.05. The 40 to 60 target exceeds this threshold while accounting for incomplete patient journeys, interrupted observation periods, and outlier cases.

This sample detects meaningful reductions in 2.6-hour average waiting time. A 15 to 20 percent reduction target of 0.4 to 0.5 hours produces effect sizes of 0.4 to 0.8, detectable with 40 to 60 observations at high power given typical standard deviations of 0.6 to 1.0 hours in healthcare waiting time studies (Karthikeyan et al., 2024). For completion rates, observing 40 to 60 cases during two to three weeks captures approximately 8 to 12 percent of monthly volume, enabling detection of 4 to 6 percentage point improvements from 92 percent to 96 percent for regular cases and 89 to 90 percent to 95 percent for rush cases.

**Limitations**  
Staff participation is voluntary and operationally constrained, potentially introducing selection bias toward technically proficient or enthusiastic staff. Mitigation includes deliberate recruitment across all departments, department head encouragement, and flexible scheduling.

External user sampling is limited to voluntary early adopters who may be more technically proficient than the general population. This limitation is inherent to technology adoption evaluation and provides valuable information about initial adoption patterns.

Patient journey observations exclude cases with abandoned processes or exceptional circumstances. Mitigation includes sampling across different days and times to capture normal operational variation and documenting reasons for incomplete observations.

The two to three week observation period per measurement phase may not capture seasonal variations. However, the focus on process-level improvements in coordination efficiency rather than volume-dependent outcomes makes short-term observation adequate for detecting system impact on targeted problems.

The sampling strategy balances statistical adequacy with operational feasibility. Sample sizes align with published healthcare information technology research methodologies (Hyzy et al., 2022; Karthikeyan et al., 2024; Mansoor et al., 2024\) and enable valid conclusions about system impact on documented operational problems.

#### **3.5.10 Research Instruments**

**System Usability Scale (SUS)**  
This standardized ten-question survey measures ease of learning, efficiency, and satisfaction using five-point scales from strongly disagree to strongly agree (Brooke, 1996). Scoring yields usability scores ranging from 0 to 100\. Hyzy et al. (2022) established through meta-analysis of 37 digital health application studies that average scores center at 68 points with standard deviation of 12.5, providing a benchmark for above-average usability. Scores above 68 indicate above-average experience; scores from 70 to 80 represent good usability; scores above 80 suggest excellent usability. The instrument is administered separately to staff dashboard users on desktop workstations, and to patient and agency portal users testing the application on their personal mobile devices, ensuring usability is validated across all intended hardware platforms.

**Custom Satisfaction Survey**  
This survey specifically addresses how the system improves patient flow visibility, facilitates result release coordination, reduces manual status checking burden, enables patient self-service progress tracking, reduces agency inquiry frequency, and provides useful email notifications. It uses five-point scales with open-ended questions for detailed feedback.

**Time-and-Motion Template**  
This structured form adapts Karthikeyan et al. (2024) healthcare workflow research methodology developed for tertiary outpatient department studies to specialized secondary clinic context, recording exact times when patients enter and exit each department, cumulative waiting periods, total cycle time from admission to result release, and observed coordination activities. It includes fields tracking regular versus rush cases enabling analysis of whether the system improves current completion rates of 92 percent for regular cases and 89 to 90 percent for rush cases. The template ensures consistent measurement across observation sessions and observers.

**Compliance Audit Checklist**  
This detailed checklist translates ISO 9001:2015, DOH Administrative Orders 2012-0012 and 2013-0006, and Data Privacy Act under Republic Act No. 10173 requirements into specific verifiable criteria for systems handling approximately 12,000 annual PEME exams and maintaining 50,000 to 70,000 active patient records. Items specify verification methods including document review, system function testing, and configuration examination. The checklist systematically verifies regulatory compliance.

#### **3.5.11 Statistical Treatment of Data**

**Descriptive Statistics**  
Patient waiting times, cycle times, and other measurements are summarized using means and standard deviations. Baseline metrics characterized include 2.6-hour average waiting time, department-specific wait times such as laboratory 65-minute peaks and radiology 55-minute peaks, percentage distributions of on-time versus late completions, incident frequencies for result collation at 224 monthly and encoding errors at 160 monthly, agency inquiry counts at 50 to 65 weekly, and email notification delivery metrics. Charts and graphs visualize patterns and changes.

**Comparison Tests**  
For continuous measurements covering waiting time, cycle time, and coordination time, paired t-tests compare pre-implementation and post-implementation values. If distributions are skewed, Wilcoxon signed-rank tests are used. For categorical outcomes covering on-time completion rates and error frequencies, McNemar tests or chi-square tests assess whether proportions improve significantly (Field, 2018).

**Effect Sizes**  
Percentage improvements provide intuitive interpretation such as cumulative patient waiting time decreased from 2.6 hours to 2.1 hours representing 19 percent reduction. Cohen's d standardizes mean differences enabling comparison against published healthcare IT intervention studies where *d* values of 0.2, 0.5, and 0.8 represent small, medium, and large effects (Cohen, 1988).

**Usability Scale Analysis**  
Individual SUS responses are scored following published Brooke (1996) methodology yielding scores from 0 to 100\. Means and standard deviations are calculated separately for staff users, patient users, and agency users. One-sample t-tests compare observed scores against a 68-point benchmark established by Hyzy et al. (2022). Item-level analysis identifies specific interface strengths and weaknesses.

**Qualitative Analysis**  
Open-ended responses and interview transcripts are systematically reviewed, identifying recurring themes about patient flow visibility, coordination efficiency, result release timeliness, progress tracking value, email notification utility, and remaining challenges. Representative quotations are selected while protecting participant privacy. Findings from different sources including surveys, interviews, observations, and system logs are compared verifying consistency and triangulating conclusions (Braun & Clarke, 2006).

All statistical analyses employ significance level *p* \> 0.05. Assumptions underlying each test are verified and violations reported transparently. Confidence intervals accompany all estimates characterizing precision and enabling judgment of operational meaningfulness.
